# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: color-depth
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:color-depth/3m-computer] The **3M computer** industrial goal was first proposed in the early 1980s by Raj Reddy and his colleagues at Carnegie Mellon University (CMU) as a minimum specification for academic and technical workstations.
[src:color-depth/3m-computer] It requires at least one megabyte of memory, a one megapixel display with 1024×1024 1-bit pixels, and one million instructions per second (MIPS) of processing power.
[src:color-depth/3m-computer] It was also often said that it should cost no more than one "megapenny" or $10,000 (equivalent to $39,000 in 2025).
[src:color-depth/3m-computer] At that time, a typical desktop computer such as an early IBM Personal Computer might have 1/8 of a megabyte of memory (128K), 1/4 of a million pixels (640 × 400 monochrome display), and run at 1/3 million instructions per second (5 MHz 8088).
[src:color-depth/3m-computer] The concept was inspired by the Xerox Alto which had been designed in the 1970s at the Xerox Palo Alto Research Center.
[src:color-depth/3m-computer] Several Alto workstations were donated to CMU, Stanford, and MIT in 1979.
[src:color-depth/3m-computer] An early 3M computer is the PERQ Workstation made by Three Rivers Computer Corporation.
[src:color-depth/3m-computer] It has a 1 million P-codes (Pascal instructions) per second processor, 256 KB of RAM (upgradeable to 1 MB), and a 768×1024 pixel display on a 15-inch (380 mm) display.
[src:color-depth/3m-computer] Though not quite a true 3M machine, it was used as the initial 3M machine for the CMU Scientific Personal Integrated Computing Environment (SPICE) workstation project.
[src:color-depth/3m-computer] The Stanford University Network SUN workstation, designed by Andy Bechtolsheim in 1980, is another example.
[src:color-depth/3m-computer] It was then commercialized by Sun Microsystems in 1982.
[src:color-depth/3m-computer] Apollo Computer (in the Route 128 region) announced the Apollo/Domain computer in 1981.
[src:color-depth/3m-computer] By 1986, CMU stated that it expected at least two companies to introduce 3M computers by the end of the year, with academic pricing of $3,000 and retail pricing of $5,000, and Stanford University planned to deploy them in computer labs.
[src:color-depth/3m-computer] The first "megapenny" 3M workstation was the Sun-2/50 diskless desktop workstation with a list price of $8,900 in 1986.
[src:color-depth/3m-computer] The original NeXT Computer was introduced in 1988 as a 3M machine by Steve Jobs, who first heard this term at Brown University.
[src:color-depth/3m-computer] The NeXT MegaPixel Display has just over 930,000 pixels with 2 bits per pixel.
[src:color-depth/3m-computer] However, floating-point performance, powered with the Motorola 68882 FPU is only about 0.25 megaflops.
[src:color-depth/3m-computer] Modern desktop computers exceed the 3M memory and speed requirements by many thousands of times, however 1080p screen pixels are only 2 times larger and 4K 8 times larger, but they are full color so each pixel uses at least 24 times as many bits.
[src:color-depth/8-bit-color] In order to turn a true color 24-bit image into an 8-bit image, the image must go through a process called color quantization.
[src:color-depth/8-bit-color] Color quantization is the process of creating a color map for a less color dense image from a more dense image.
[src:color-depth/8-bit-color] The simplest form of quantization is to simply assign 3 bits to red, 3 bits to green and 2 bits to blue, as the human eye is less sensitive to blue light.
[src:color-depth/8-bit-color] There could be different groupings of colors that make evenly spreading the colors out inefficient and likely to misrepresent the actual image.
[src:color-depth/8-bit-color] An alternative approach is to use a palette, with each of the 256 possible indexes pointing towards a larger color space (ex: 256 colors chosen from 4096).
[src:color-depth/8-bit-color] Because the color map doesn't need to have every color in it and just needs to accurately represent the more color dense image, an arbitrary color can be assigned to each of the 256 available color indexes on the map.
[src:color-depth/8-bit-color] Popular approaches for creating these maps (also known as palettes) include the *popularity algorithm* which chooses the 256 most common colors and creates a map from them.
[src:color-depth/8-bit-color] The more accurate *median cut* algorithm resorts and divides colors to find the median of different color groups resulting in a more accurate final color map.
[src:color-depth/8-bit-color] Because of the low amount of memory and resultant higher speeds of 8-bit color images, 8-bit color was a common ground among computer graphics development until more memory and higher CPU speeds became readily available to consumers.
[src:color-depth/8-bit-color] The VGA standard for graphical interface used a redefinable 256 color (8-bit) color palette, although these were selected from an 18-bit (6-bit per RGB channel, 262,144 colors) gamut.
[src:color-depth/8-bit-color] Developed in 1987 by IBM, the VGA interface supported a maximum resolution of 640x480 pixels.
[src:color-depth/8-bit-color] Due to this legacy, some image types such as GIF and TIFF use an 8-bit color palette system to store data.
[src:color-depth/8-bit-color] Even though it is now outdated for most consumer applications, 8-bit color encoding can still be useful in imaging systems with limited data bandwidth or memory capacity.
[src:color-depth/8-bit-color] For example, both Mars Exploration Rovers used an 8-bit grayscale format for navigation imaging.
[src:color-depth/8-bit-color] Due to the nature of the 8-bit system, most images have different color maps.
[src:color-depth/8-bit-color] Since an 8-bit color display can not display two images with different color maps at the same time, it is usually impossible to display two different 8-bit images on the same such display at the same time.
[src:color-depth/8-bit-color] In practice, in order to avoid this problem, most images do not use the full range of 256 colors.
[src:color-depth/8-bit-color] Currently, most graphics hardware runs in 24-bit truecolor or 32-bit truecolor (24-bit truecolor and an 8-bit alpha channel).
[src:color-depth/8-bit-color] However, some remote desktop software (Virtual Network Computing, Remote Desktop Protocol) can switch to 8-bit color to conserve bandwidth.
[src:color-depth/8-bit-color] With the comparative low cost and high speeds of modern computers, some image editing is even done in a raw format with anywhere from 12 to 14 bits from each of the camera's image sensor pixels in order to avoid image quality reduction while editing.
[src:color-depth/achromatopsia] The syndrome is typically first noticed in children around six months of age due to their photophobia or their nystagmus.
[src:color-depth/achromatopsia] The nystagmus becomes less noticeable with age but the other symptoms of the syndrome become more relevant as school age approaches.
[src:color-depth/achromatopsia] Visual acuity and stability of the eye motions generally improve during the first six to seven years of life – but remain near 20/200.
[src:color-depth/achromatopsia] Otherwise the syndrome is considered stationary and does not worsen with age.
[src:color-depth/achromatopsia] If the light level during testing is optimized, achromats may achieve corrected visual acuity of 20/100 to 20/150 at lower light levels, regardless of the absence of color.
[src:color-depth/achromatopsia] The fundus of the eye appears completely normal.
[src:color-depth/achromatopsia] Achromatopsia can be classified as *complete* or *incomplete*.
[src:color-depth/achromatopsia] In general, symptoms of incomplete achromatopsia are attenuated versions of those of complete achromatopsia.
[src:color-depth/achromatopsia] Individuals with incomplete achromatopsia have reduced visual acuity with or without nystagmus or photophobia.
[src:color-depth/achromatopsia] Incomplete achromats show only partial impairment of cone cell function.
[src:color-depth/achromatopsia] Achromatopsia is sometimes called **rod monochromacy** (as opposed to blue cone monochromacy), as achromats exhibit a complete absence of cone cell activity via electroretinography in photopic lighting.
[src:color-depth/achromatopsia] The hemeralopic aspect of achromatopsia can be diagnosed non-invasively using electroretinography.
[src:color-depth/achromatopsia] The response at low (scotopic) and median (mesopic) light levels will be normal but the response under high light level (photopic) conditions will be absent.
[src:color-depth/achromatopsia] The mesopic level is approximately a hundred times lower than the clinical level used for the typical high level electroretinogram.
[src:color-depth/achromatopsia] When as described; the condition is due to a saturation in the neural portion of the retina and not due to the absence of the photoreceptors per se.
[src:color-depth/achromatopsia] In general, the molecular pathomechanism of achromatopsia is either the inability to properly control or respond to altered levels of cGMP; particularly important in visual perception as its level controls the opening of cyclic nucleotide-gated ion channels (CNGs).
[src:color-depth/achromatopsia] Decreasing the concentration of cGMP results in closure of CNGs and resulting hyperpolarization and cessation of glutamate release.
[src:color-depth/achromatopsia] Native retinal CNGs are composed of 2 α- and 2 β-subunits, which are CNGA3 and CNGB3, respectively, in cone cells.
[src:color-depth/achromatopsia] When expressed alone, CNGB3 cannot produce functional channels, whereas this is not the case for CNGA3.
[src:color-depth/achromatopsia] Coassembly of CNGA3 and CNGB3 produces channels with altered membrane expression, ion permeability (Na+ vs.
[src:color-depth/achromatopsia] K+ and Ca2+), relative efficacy of cAMP/cGMP activation, decreased outward rectification, current flickering, and sensitivity to block by L-cis-diltiazem.
[src:color-depth/achromatopsia] Mutations tend to result in the loss of CNGB3 function or gain of function—often increased affinity for cGMP—of CNGA3. cGMP levels are controlled by the activity of the cone cell transducin, GNAT2.
[src:color-depth/achromatopsia] Mutations in GNAT2 tend to result in a truncated and, presumably, non-functional protein, thereby preventing alteration of cGMP levels by photons.
[src:color-depth/achromatopsia] There is a positive correlation between the severity of mutations in these proteins and the completeness of the achromatopsia phenotype.
[src:color-depth/achromatopsia] Molecular diagnosis can be established by identification of biallelic variants in the causative genes.
[src:color-depth/achromatopsia] Molecular genetic testing approaches used in achromatopsia can include targeted analysis for the common CNGB3 variant c.1148delC (p.Thr383IlefsTer13), use of a multigenerational panel, or comprehensive genomic testing.
[src:color-depth/achromatopsia] While some mutations in CNGA3 result in truncated and, presumably, non-functional channels this is largely not the case.
[src:color-depth/achromatopsia] While few mutations have received in-depth study, at least one mutation does result in functional channels.
[src:color-depth/achromatopsia] Curiously, this mutation, T369S, produces profound alterations when expressed without CNGB3.
[src:color-depth/achromatopsia] One such alteration is decreased affinity for cyclic guanosine monophosphate.
[src:color-depth/achromatopsia] Others include the introduction of a sub-conductance, altered single-channel gating kinetics, and increased calcium permeability.
[src:color-depth/achromatopsia] When mutant T369S channels coassemble with CNGB3, however, the only remaining aberration is increased calcium permeability.
[src:color-depth/achromatopsia] While it is not immediately clear how this increase in Ca2+ leads to achromatopsia, one hypothesis is that this increased current decreases the signal-to-noise ratio.
[src:color-depth/achromatopsia] Other characterized mutations, such as Y181C and the other S1 region mutations, result in decreased current density due to an inability of the channel to traffic to the surface.
[src:color-depth/achromatopsia] Such loss of function will undoubtedly negate the cone cell's ability to respond to visual input and produce achromatopsia.
[src:color-depth/achromatopsia] At least one other missense mutation outside of the S1 region, T224R, also leads to loss of function.
[src:color-depth/achromatopsia] While very few mutations in CNGB3 have been characterized, the vast majority of them result in truncated channels that are presumably non-functional.
[src:color-depth/achromatopsia] This will largely result in haploinsufficiency, though in some cases the truncated proteins may be able to coassemble with wild-type channels in a dominant negative fashion.
[src:color-depth/achromatopsia] The most prevalent ACHM3 mutation, T383IfsX12, results in a non-functional truncated protein that does not properly traffic to the cell membrane.
[src:color-depth/achromatopsia] The three missense mutations that have received further study show a number of aberrant properties, with one underlying theme.
[src:color-depth/achromatopsia] The R403Q mutation, which lies in the pore region of the channel, results in an increase in outward current rectification, versus the largely linear current-voltage relationship of wild-type channels, concomitant with an increase in cGMP affinity.
[src:color-depth/achromatopsia] The other mutations show either increased (S435F) or decreased (F525N) surface expression but also with increased affinity for cAMP and cGMP.
[src:color-depth/achromatopsia] It is the increased affinity for cGMP and cAMP in these mutants that is likely the disorder-causing change.
[src:color-depth/achromatopsia] Such increased affinity will result in channels that are insensitive to the slight concentration changes of cGMP due to light input into the retina.
[src:color-depth/achromatopsia] Upon activation by light, cone opsin causes the exchange of GDP for GTP in the guanine nucleotide binding protein (G-protein) α-transducing activity polypeptide 2 (GNAT2).
[src:color-depth/achromatopsia] This causes the release of the activated α-subunit from the inhibitory β/γ-subunits.
[src:color-depth/achromatopsia] This α-subunit then activates a phosphodiesterase that catalyzes the conversion of cGMP to GMP, thereby reducing current through CNG3 channels.
[src:color-depth/achromatopsia] As this process is absolutely vital for proper color processing it is not surprising that mutations in GNAT2 lead to achromatopsia.
[src:color-depth/achromatopsia] The known mutations in this gene, all result in truncated proteins.
[src:color-depth/achromatopsia] Presumably, then, these proteins are non-functional and, consequently, cone opsin that has been activated by light does not lead to altered cGMP levels or photoreceptor membrane hyperpolarization.
[src:color-depth/achromatopsia] As achromatopsia is linked to only a few single-gene mutations, it is a good candidate for gene therapy.
[src:color-depth/achromatopsia] Gene therapy is a technique for injecting functional genes into the cells that need them, replacing or overruling the original alleles linked to achromatopsia, thereby curing it – at least in part.
[src:color-depth/achromatopsia] Achromatopsia has been a focus of gene therapy since 2010, when achromatopsia in dogs was partially cured.
[src:color-depth/achromatopsia] Several clinical trials on humans are ongoing with mixed results.
[src:color-depth/achromatopsia] In July 2023, a study found positive but limited improvements on congenital CNGA3 achromatopsia.
[src:color-depth/achromatopsia] Since 2003, a cybernetic device called the eyeborg has allowed people to perceive color through sound waves.
[src:color-depth/achromatopsia] This form of sensory substitution maps the hue perceived by a camera worn on the head to a pitch experienced through bone conduction according to a sonochromatic scale.
[src:color-depth/achromatopsia] This allows achromats (or even the totally blind) to perceive – or estimate – the color of an object.
[src:color-depth/achromatopsia] Achromat and artist Neil Harbisson was the first to use the eyeborg in early 2004, which allowed him to start painting in color.
[src:color-depth/achromatopsia] He has since acted as a spokesperson for the technology, namely in a 2012 TED Talk.
[src:color-depth/achromatopsia] A 2015 study suggests that achromats who use the Eyeborg for several years exhibit neural plasticity, which indicates the sensory substitution has become intuitive for them.
[src:color-depth/achromatopsia] Achromatopsia is a relatively uncommon disorder, with a prevalence of 1 in 30,000 people.
[src:color-depth/achromatopsia] However, on the small Micronesian atoll of Pingelap, approximately five percent of the atoll's 3,000 inhabitants are affected.
[src:color-depth/achromatopsia] This is the result of a population bottleneck caused by a typhoon and ensuing famine in the 1770s, which killed all but about twenty islanders, including one who was heterozygous for achromatopsia.
[src:color-depth/achromatopsia] The people of this region have termed achromatopsia "maskun", which literally means "not see" in Pingelapese.
[src:color-depth/achromatopsia] This unusual population drew neurologist Oliver Sacks to the island for which he wrote his 1997 book, *The Island of the Colorblind*.
[src:color-depth/achromatopsia] Blue cone monochromacy (BCM) is another genetic condition causing monochromacy.
[src:color-depth/achromatopsia] It mimics many of the symptoms of incomplete achromatopsia and before the discovery of its molecular biological basis was commonly referred to as *x-linked achromatopsia*, *sex-linked achromatopsia* or *atypical achromatopsia*.
[src:color-depth/achromatopsia] BCM stems from mutations or deletions of the OPN1LW and OPN1MW genes, both on the X chromosome.
[src:color-depth/achromatopsia] As a recessive x-linked condition, BCM disproportionately affects males, unlike typical achromatopsia.
[src:color-depth/achromatopsia] Cerebral achromatopsia is a form of acquired color blindness that is caused by damage to the cerebral cortex.
[src:color-depth/achromatopsia] Damage is most commonly localized to visual area V4 of the visual cortex (the major part of the colour center), which receives information from the parvocellular pathway involved in color processing.
[src:color-depth/achromatopsia] It is most frequently caused by physical trauma, hemorrhage or tumor tissue growth.
[src:color-depth/achromatopsia] If there is unilateral damage, a loss of color perception in only half of the visual field may result; this is known as hemiachromatopsia.
[src:color-depth/achromatopsia] Cerebral achromats usually do not experience the other major symptoms of congenital achromatopsia, since photopic vision still functions.
[src:color-depth/achromatopsia] Color agnosia involves having difficulty recognizing colors, while still being able to perceive them as measured by a color matching or categorizing task.
[src:color-depth/achromatopsia] Complete lack of the perception of color in a subject, seeing only in black, white, and shades of grey.
[src:color-depth/achromatopsia] Reduced visual capacity in bright light, i.e. day-blindness.
[src:color-depth/achromatopsia] Term to describe both normal and pathological conditions related to the oculomotor system.
[src:color-depth/achromatopsia] is quite noticeable and the frequency of the oscillation tends to be quite low.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] The **Acorn Archimedes** is a family of personal computers designed by Acorn Computers of Cambridge, England.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] The systems in this family use Acorn's own ARM architecture processors and initially ran the Arthur operating system, with later models introducing RISC OS and, in a separate workstation range, RISC iX.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] The first Archimedes models were introduced in 1987, and systems in the Archimedes family were sold until the mid-1990s alongside Acorn's newer Risc PC and A7000 models.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] The first Archimedes models, featuring a 32-bit ARM2 RISC CPU running at 8 MHz, provided a significant upgrade from Acorn's previous machines and 8-bit home computers in general.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] Acorn's publicity claimed a performance rating of 4 MIPS.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] Later models featured the ARM3 CPU, delivering a substantial performance improvement, and the first ARM system-on-a-chip, the ARM250.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] The Archimedes preserves a degree of compatibility with Acorn's earlier machines, offering BBC BASIC, support for running 8-bit applications, and display modes compatible with those earlier machines.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] Following on from Acorn's involvement with the BBC Micro, two of the first models—the A305 and A310—were given BBC branding.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] The name "Acorn Archimedes" is commonly used to describe any of Acorn's contemporary designs based on the same architecture.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] This architecture can be broadly characterised as involving the ARM CPU and the first generation chipset consisting of MEMC (MEMory Controller), VIDC (VIDeo and sound Controller) and IOC (Input Output Controller).
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] Having introduced the BBC Micro in 1981, Acorn established itself as a major supplier to primary and secondary education in the United Kingdom.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] However, attempts to replicate this dominance in other sectors, such as home computing with the BBC Micro and Acorn Electron, and in other markets, including the United States and West Germany, were less successful.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] As microprocessor and computing technology advanced in the early 1980s, microcomputer manufacturers had to consider evolving their product lines to offer increased capabilities and performance.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] Acorn's strategy for business computing and development of more capable machines involved a range of "second processor" expansions, including a Z80 second processor running the CP/M operating system, a commitment made by Acorn when securing the BBC Micro contract.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] Meanwhile, established platforms like CP/M running on Z80 processors faced competition from the IBM PC running PC DOS and computers with a variety of operating systems on Intel processors such as the 8088 and 8086.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] Systems using the Motorola 68000 and other processors running the Unix operating system also became available.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] Apple launched the Lisa and Macintosh computers, and Digital Research introduced its own GEM graphical user interface software, building on previous work by Xerox.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] Acorn's strategy seemingly evolved to align with Torch Computers—a company that Acorn considered acquiring—which had already combined BBC Micro hardware with second processors (and modems) to produce their Communicator product line and derivatives.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] In 1984, Acorn introduced the Acorn Business Computer (ABC) range, based on the BBC Micro architecture, offering models with different second processors and capabilities to respond to computing trends at the time.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] These models received generally favorable reviews from the computing press.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] However, with Acorn facing financial strain, the company was rescued by Olivetti in 1985, leaving the ABC's future uncertain in the expected restructuring process.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] Ultimately, only one of the variants—the Acorn Cambridge Workstation—would reach the market, in a somewhat different form than originally planned.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] The demise of the Acorn Business Computer left Acorn purely with a range of 8-bit microcomputer products, leaving the company vulnerable to competitors introducing 16-bit and 32-bit machines.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] The increasing dominance of MS-DOS in the business market and advocacy for the use of such software in the education sector left Acorn at risk of potential exclusion from its core market.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] Meanwhile, competing machines attempted to offer a degree of compatibility with the BBC Micro, enticing schools to upgrade to newer, more powerful non-Acorn machines while retaining access to software developed and purchased for Acorn's "aging machine".
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] Disillusionment was sufficient for some software producers to signal a withdrawal from the Acorn market.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] Other commentators who responded to the B+ suggested that Acorn pursue the second processor strategy more aggressively, leveraging the existing user base of the BBC Micro while those users were still using the machine.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] In 1986, Acorn introduced the BBC Master series, starting with the Master 128 which re-emphasised second processors in the form of internally fitted "co-processors".
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] Although a modest evolution of the existing 6502-based platform, enthusiasm for the series was somewhat greater than that for the B+ models, with dealers and software developers citing the expansion capabilities and improved compatibility over the B+.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] However, the competitiveness of these co-processors proved to be constrained by hardware limitations, compatibility and pricing, with a Master 512 system featuring a Master 128 and 80186 co-processor comparing unfavourably to complete IBM PC-compatible systems.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] The planned Master Scientific product was never launched, leaving potential customers with the existing Cambridge Co-Processor expansion as their only available option.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] Attitudes towards Acorn and its technological position changed somewhat in late 1985 as news of its RISC microprocessor development effort emerged, potentially encouraging Olivetti to continue its support for the company at "a critical stage" in its refinancing of Acorn.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] Subsequent commentary suggested the availability of this microprocessor—the Acorn RISC Machine—in future computers as well as in an evaluation board for the BBC Micro, although such a board—the ARM Evaluation System—would only be announced in mid-1986 at a cost of £4500.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] Having also developed the additional support chips required to make up a complete microcomputer, Acorn was regarded as having leapt ahead of its nearest competitors.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] Powered by an ARM2 (Acorn RISC Machine) processor, the Acorn Archimedes was variously described as "the first RISC machine inexpensive enough for home use", and "the first commercially-available RISC-based microcomputer".
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] The first models were released in June 1987, as the 300 and 400 series.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] The 400 series included four expansion slots and an ST-506 controller for an internal hard drive, whereas the 300 series required the addition of a backplane to gain expansion slot capabilities.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] A two slot backplane could be added to the 300 series as an official upgrade, with the possibility of 4-slot backplane being available from third parties, but a hard drive expansion card was also required for these machines, occupying one slot.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] All models featured eight-channel 8-bit stereo sound and were capable of displaying 256 colours on screen.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] Three models were initially released with different amounts of memory, the A305, A310 and A440.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] The 400 series models were replaced in 1989 by the A410/1, the A420/1 and A440/1, these featuring an upgraded MEMC1a and RISC OS.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] Earlier models which shipped with Arthur could be upgraded to RISC OS 2 by replacing the ROM chip containing the operating system.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] Because the ROM chips contained the operating system, the computer booted instantly into its GUI system, familiar from the Atari ST.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] Despite the A310 being limited to 1 MB of RAM officially, several companies made upgrades to 2 MB and 4 MB, with the smaller upgrades augmenting the built-in RAM and the larger upgrades replacing it entirely.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] The 400 series were officially limited to 4 MB of RAM, but several companies released 8 MB upgrades that provided an extra MEMC chip plus 4 MB of RAM to complement an existing 4 MB of fitted RAM.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] In early 1989, speculation about new machines in the Archimedes range envisaged a low-cost, cut-down model with 512 KB of RAM to replace the A305 in a fashion reminiscent of the Master Compact.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] This speculation evolved to more accurately predict a machine with 1 MB of RAM aimed at junior or primary schools.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] Other commentators correctly predicted the provision of an internal disc drive and a single "special" podule slot.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] However, any new, low-cost product providing support for up to 2 MB of RAM also raised questions about the future of the 300 series, given the limitation of the 300 series to a maximum of 1 MB at that time.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] Concurrently with these rumoured product development efforts, work had commenced on a successor to the Arthur operating system, initially named Arthur 2 but renamed to RISC OS 2 for launch.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] In May 1989, a number of new machines were introduced along with RISC OS 2: the 300 series was phased out in favour of the new BBC A3000, and the 400 series were replaced by the improved 400/1 series models.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] The A3000 used an 8 MHz ARM2 and was supplied with 1 MB of RAM and RISC OS on 512 KB of ROM.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] Unlike the previous models, the A3000 came in a single-part case similar to the BBC Micro, Amiga 500 and Atari ST computers, with the keyboard and disc drive integrated into a base unit "slightly smaller than the Master 128".
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] Despite the machine's desktop footprint, being larger than a simple keyboard, the case was not designed to support a monitor.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] Acorn offered a monitor stand that attached to the machine, this being bundled with Acorn's Learning Curve package, and PRES announced a monitor plinth and external disc drive case.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] The new model sported only a single internal expansion slot, which was physically different from that of the earlier models, although electrically similar.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] An external connector could interface to existing expansion cards, with an external case for such cards being recommended and anticipated at the machine's launch, and one such solution subsequently being provided by PRES's expansion system.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] Acorn announced a combined user port and MIDI expansion for the internal slot at the machine's launch, priced at £49.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] To enable the machine's serial port, an upgrade costing £19 was required, and Econet support was also an optional extra.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] Simtec Electronics even offered a RAM upgrade to 8 MB for the A3000 alongside other models.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] In 1996, IFEL announced a memory upgrade for the A3000 utilising a generic 72-pin SIMM module to provide 4 MB of RAM.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] Hard drive expansions based on ST506, SCSI and IDE technologies were also offered by a range of vendors.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] The retail price of £649 plus VAT was considered an "expensive alternative" to the intended competition—the Commodore Amiga and Atari ST—but many times faster than similarly priced models of those ranges.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] The Amiga 500, it was noted, cost a "not-so-bargain" £550 once upgraded to 1 MB of RAM.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] The relative affordability of the A3000 compared to the first Archimedes machines and the release of RISC OS helped to convince educational software producers of the viability of the platform.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] Shortly after the A3000's launch, one local education authority had already ordered 500 machines, aiming to introduce the A3000 to its primary schools in addition to other levels of education.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] Such was the success of the model that it alone had 37 percent of the UK schools market in a nine-month period in 1991 and, by the end of that year, was estimated to represent 15 percent of the 500,000 or more computers installed in the country's schools.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] The appeal of the A3000 to education may also have motivated the return of Microvitec to the Acorn market with the Cub3000 monitor: a re-engineered version of the Cub monitor that was popular amongst institutional users of the original BBC Micro.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] The introduction of the A3000 also saw Acorn regaining a presence in mainstream retail channels, through a deal with high street retailer Dixons to sell the computer at "business centre" outlets, followed by agreements with the John Lewis and Alders chains.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] Acorn also sought to secure the interest of games publishers, hosting a conference in August 1989 for representatives of "the top 30 software houses, including Ocean, Domark, US Gold, Grand Slam and Electronic Arts".
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] The software, having a retail value of around £200, consisted of the second, RISC OS compliant version of Acorn's First Word Plus, the hypermedia application Genesis, and the PC Emulator software, with an introductory video presented by Fred Harris, formerly of *Micro Live*.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] Aiming at the "pre-Christmas market" in 1990, another bundle called Jet Set offered a more entertainment-focused collection of software valued at £200 including Clares' Interdictor flight simulator, Domark's Trivial Pursuit, Superior Golf, and the Euclid 3D modelling package from Ace Computing.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] The price of this bundle was £747.50 which also included a television modulator developed by the bundle's distributor, ZCL, designed for use with "any TV set" and offering a "monitor quality" picture.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] Pre-launch speculation for the A3000 had suggested the inclusion of a TV modulator and a possible price of £399 for a 512 KB "Archimedes 205" machine aimed at the home market.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] Rumours about the integration of various elements of Acorn's chipset—specifically, MEMC and VIDC—to "do an Electron" were regarded as logistically demanding and thus unlikely to reduce cost.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] Such increased integration and targeting of the home market was later pursued with the introduction of the A3010 in 1992.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] The A540, introduced in late 1990, was an anticipated consequence of Acorn's Unix workstation development, offering the same general specification as Acorn's R260 Unix workstation (running RISC iX) but without built-in Ethernet support and running RISC OS 2 instead of Unix.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] It was Acorn's first machine to be fitted with the ARM3 processor as standard, supporting up to 16 MB of RAM, and included higher speed SCSI and provision for connecting genlock devices.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] The memory access frequency was raised to 12 MHz in the A540, compared to 8 MHz in earlier models, thus providing enhanced system performance over earlier models upgraded with ARM3 processors.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] The hardware design featured memory modules, each providing their own memory controller and 4 MB of RAM, and a processor module providing the ARM3 and including a slot for a floating point accelerator (FPA) chip, the latter offering the possibility (subsequently unrealised) of processor upgrades.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] The FPA, replacing Acorn's previous floating point podule, was scheduled to be available in 1991.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] Much delayed, the FPA finally became available in 1993.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] In late 1991, the A5000 was launched to replace the A440/1 machine in the existing product range.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] The A5000 initially ran RISC OS 3.0, although after bug fixes most shipped with RISC OS 3.10 or 3.11.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] The A5000 featured the new 25 MHz ARM3 processor, 2 or 4 MB of RAM, either a 40 MB or an 80 MB hard drive and a more conventional pizza box-style two-part case.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] With IBM-compatible PCs offering increasingly better graphical capabilities, they had not merely matched the capabilities of Acorn's machines, but in offering resolutions of 1024 × 768 in 16 or 256 colours and with 24-bit palettes, they had surpassed them.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] The A5000 was the first Acorn to adopt a 15-pin VGA connector and (along with the earlier A540) supported the SVGA resolution of 800 × 600 in 16 colours, although the observation that "Archimedes machines have simply not kept pace" arguably remained.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] Earlier models could also benefit from the video performance of the A5000 via third party upgrades such as the Computer Concepts ColourCard Gold.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] It was also the first Archimedes to feature a high density capable floppy disc drive as standard.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] This natively supported various formats including MS-DOS and Atari ST discs with formatted capacities of 720 KB and 1.44 MB.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] The native ADFS floppy format had a slightly larger capacity of 800 KB for double density or 1.6 MB for high density.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] Later A5000s featured a 33 MHz ARM3, 2 or 4 MB of RAM, and an 80 or 160 MB hard drive.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] Particularly useful in this revised A5000 was the use of a socket for the MEMC1a chip, meaning that memory expansions beyond 4 MB could more easily replace the single MEMC1a, plugging in a card providing the two MEMC1a devices required to support 8 MB.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] Earlier A5000s required desoldering of the fitted MEMC1a to provide such a socket.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] In 1992, Acorn introduced the A4 laptop computer featuring a slower 24 MHz version of the ARM3 processor (compared to the 25 MHz ARM3 in the A5000), supporting a 6 MHz power-saving mode, and providing between 2.5 and 4 hours of usage on battery power.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] The machine featured a 9-inch passive matrix LCD screen capable of displaying a maximum resolution of 640 × 480 pixels in 15 levels of grey, also featuring a monitor port which offered the same display capabilities as an A5000.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] A notable omission from the machine was a built-in pointing device, requiring users to navigate with the cursor keys or attach a conventional Acorn three-button mouse, such as the Logitech mouse bundled with the machine.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] Other expansion ports available on the A4 were serial and parallel ports, a PS/2 connector for an external keyboard, a headphone connector, and support for an Econet expansion (as opposed to an Econet port itself).
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] No other provision for expansion was made beyond the fitting of the Econet card and a hard drive.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] Just as the processor could be slowed down to save power, so the 12 MHz RAM could be slowed to 3 MHz, with various subsystems also being switched off as appropriate, and with power saving being activated after "more than a second or so" of user inactivity.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] The A4's case itself was used by Olivetti and Triumph-Adler models, particularly the Triumph-Adler Walkstation which did integrate a built-in pointing device, this being described as an "all-but-unusable touchpad mouse-controller" by one reviewer.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] Launch pricing of the A4 set the entry-level model with 2 MB of RAM at £1399 plus VAT, with the higher-tier model with 4 MB of RAM and 60 MB hard drive at £1699 plus VAT.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] Education pricing was £1099 and £1399 respectively.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] Peripherals for the A4 were eventually produced, with Acorn providing the previously announced Econet card, and with Atomwide providing Ethernet and SCSI adapters utilising the bidirectional parallel port present on the A4 (and also the A5000 and later machines).
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] Atomwide also offered the "Hi-Point" trackball peripheral modified to work as an Acorn-compatible mouse which attached to the side of the unit.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] In 1992, several new models were introduced to complement the A3000 and to replace the low-end A400 series models: the A3010, A3020 and A4000.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] Launched alongside the Acorn Pocket Book, a distinct product based on the Psion Series 3, the machines heralded "a changed company, with new direction" and the availability of Acorn products in mainstream high street stores including Dixons, John Lewis and Argos as well as mail order catalogues.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] Thus, a transition had begun from a range of machines of different vintages that still included the A3000 (at the low end) and the A540 (at the high end) to a range that purely featured more recently designed models including the A5000 as the high-end offering and the A4 portable.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] These new models utilised the first ARM system-on-a-chip—the ARM250 microprocessor—a single-chip design including the functionality of an ARM2 (or ARM3 without cache), the IOC1, VIDC1a and MEMC1a chips all "integrated into a single giant chip" and fabricated using a 1 micron process.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] The ARM250, running at a higher 12 MHz clock frequency and used in conjunction with faster 80ns memory chips, compared to the 8 MHz of the ARM2 and the 125ns memory of the A3000, gave a potential 50% performance increase over such older systems, achieving a reported 7 MIPS.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] Some early units of the A3010 did not actually utilise the ARM250, instead embodying a "mezzanine" board carrying the four separate devices comprising the complete chipset, with this board plugged into the motherboard in place of the ARM250.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] One inadvertent advantage that the mezzanine board conferred was the ability to upgrade the ARM2 on the board to an ARM3, this being a popular upgrade for previous ARM2-based models that was incompatible with the ARM250.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] However, performing such an upgrade involves modifications to both the "Adelaide" mezzanine board and the ARM3 upgrade board employed in the refit.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] For machines fitted with an actual ARM250 processor, the closest alternative to an ARM3 upgrade in terms of performance enhancement was the Simtec "Turbo RAM" upgrade which provided 4 MB of faster RAM and gave a 40 percent improvement in overall system performance.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] These machines were supplied with RISC OS 3.10 or 3.11.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] The A30x0 series had a one-piece design, similar to the A3000 but slightly more shallow, while the A4000 looked like a slightly slimmer A5000.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] Meanwhile, the A4000 was aimed at the secondary education and office markets, offering a separate adjustable keyboard to comply with ergonomics regulations deemed applicable to these users.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] Technically, the A4000 was almost functionally identical to the A3020, only differing in the supported hard disk size (3.5-inch in the A4000), this due to the machine's different casing.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] Despite the resemblance to the A5000, the A4000 along with the other models only provided a single "mini-podule" expansion slot, just as the A3000 did.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] All three ARM250-based machines could be upgraded to 4 MB with plug-in chips: though the A3010 was designed for 2 MB, third party upgrades overcame this.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] In 1996, IFEL announced a memory upgrade for the range utilising a generic 72-pin SIMM module to provide 4 MB of RAM.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] Pricing started at just under £500 including VAT for the Family Solution bundle: an unexpanded A3010 with no monitor (to be used with a television), combined with the EasiWord word processor and one game (initially *Quest for Gold*).
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] The existing Learning Curve bundle, updated to incorporate the A3010 upgraded to 2 MB of RAM in place of the A3000, included an Acorn colour monitor, the PC Emulator and a suite of Genesis hypermedia applications for a price of £799.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] The A4000 Home Office bundle combined the A4000 with Acorn colour monitor, Icon Technology's EasiWriter 2 "professional word processor" and Iota's Desktop Database application for a price of around £1175.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] The retail pricing of the A3010 was notable as making it the cheapest of any Archimedes machine sold.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] In 1993, Commodore would subsequently offer the entry-level Amiga 600 at a price of only £199, although with Commodore "losing money on a big scale" while Acorn remained profitable, such discounting was not regarded as a threat to the A3010.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] The pricing and bundles involving these machines were updated in late 1993, introducing a new Action Pack in place of the Family Solution, featuring the game Zool plus Icon Technology's StartWrite word processor.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] This bundle effectively reduced the price of the A3010 to £399 including VAT, reportedly making it "the cheapest Risc machine yet".
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] The Learning Curve was revised to feature Acorn's own Advance integrated suite, together with the PC Emulator and DR DOS 6, and the bundle was also made available in conjunction with the A4000.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] The Home Office bundle was updated with Iota's DataPower replacing Desktop Database, and with Colton Software's PipeDream 4 and Acorn's PC Emulator being added to augment EasiWriter.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] A variety of demonstration programs and an audio training tape were also provided with the bundles.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] At the time of these product revisions, the A3020 had become absent from related promotional material, even material aimed at the educational purchaser, although it remained in Acorn's price list presumably for the interest of institutional purchasers.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] Acorn's marketing relationships with high street retailers were somewhat problematic.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] While outlets such as the John Lewis Partnership proved to be successful marketing partners, electrical retailer Dixons seemingly made relatively little effort to sell Acorn machines despite promising "greater opportunities" in 1993 after earlier criticism.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] In late 1994, Acorn appointed a sole distributor for the A3010 Action Pack and Learning Curve bundles, with the pricing of the former reduced to only £299.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] Persisting with the strategy that some purchasers might choose a product positioned between games consoles and traditional PC-compatibles, the distributor, ZCL, aimed to take advantage of the absence of Commodore during the Christmas 1994 season.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] As the Christmas 1995 season approached, Beebug purchased Acorn's "entire remaining inventory", offering the machine for £135 including VAT together with various "value-added packs".
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] Production of the A3020 and A4000 ceased in 1995, with remaining stocks to be sold during 1996, due to their lack of conformance with newly introduced European Union electrical and electronics regulations.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] This left the A7000 as Acorn's entry-level desktop system, and appropriate pricing adjustments were expected, particularly as faster versions of the A7000 were anticipated (and eventually delivered in the form of the A7000+).
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] The *A7000*, despite its name being reminiscent of the Archimedes naming conventions, was actually more similar to the Risc PC, the line of RISC OS computers that succeeded the Archimedes in 1994.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p01] It lacked, however, the DEBI expansion slots and multi-slice case that characterized the Risc PC (though by removing the CD-ROM drive, a backplane with one slot could be fitted).
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Reminiscent of the BBC Micro upon its release, the earliest Archimedes models were delivered with provisional versions of the Arthur operating system, for which upgrades were apparently issued free of charge, thus avoiding the controversy around early ROM upgrades for the BBC Micro.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] In early 1988, Arthur 1.2 was delivered in an attempt to fix the deficiencies and problems in the earlier versions of the software.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] However, even after Arthur 1.2 had been released, a reported 100 documented bugs regarded as "mostly quite obscure" persisted, with Acorn indicating that a "new, enhanced version" of the operating system was under development.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Following on from the release of Arthur 1.2, Acorn itself offered a "basic word processor", ArcWriter, intended for "personal correspondence, notices and short articles" and to demonstrate the window, menu and pointer features of the system, employing built-in printer fonts for rapid printed output.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] The software was issued free of charge for registered users, although Acorn indicated that it would not produce a "definitive" word processor for the platform, in contrast to the BBC Micro where the View word processor had been central to Acorn's office software range.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] However, Acorn did also announce a port of the 1st Word package, First Word Plus, for the platform.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] ArcWriter was poorly received, with window repainting issues demonstrated as a particular problem, and with users complaining of "serious bugs".
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Although taking advantage of the Arthur desktop environment and using anti-aliased fonts, complaints were made about "blurred and smudged" characters and slow display updates when changing fonts or styles on low-memory machines like the A305.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] An early competitor, Graphic Writer, was received more favourably but provided its own full-screen user interface.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Neither were regarded as competitive with established products on other platforms.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Several software companies immediately promised software for the Archimedes, most notably Computer Concepts, Clares and Minerva, with Advanced Memory Systems, BBC Soft and Logotron being other familiar software publishers.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Autodesk, Grafox and GST were newcomers to the Acorn market.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] However, in early 1988, many software developers were reportedly holding off on releasing software for the Archimedes until the release of a stable operating system, with Acorn offering to lend Arthur 1.2 to developers.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Claims had been made of confusion amongst potential purchasers of the machine caused by the lack of available software, with Acorn having pursued a strategy of launching the machine first so that independent software developers might have hardware to work with.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] In order to make the Archimedes more attractive to certain sectors, Acorn announced a £250,000 investment in educational software and indicated a commitment to business software development.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Alongside First Word Plus, the Logistix spreadsheet-based business planning package was also commissioned by Acorn from Grafox Limited as a port to the platform.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Autodesk released AutoSketch for the Archimedes in 1988, having launched the product in March the same year.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Priced at £79 plus VAT, it offered the precision drawing functionality familiar from AutoCad but with "none of the frills" that made the latter product professionally suitable for various markets at pricing that could exceed £2500.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] On the Archimedes, AutoSketch was reported to run at about five times the speed of a "standard PC-compatible machine".
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Although Acorn had restricted itself to supporting the use of its View word processor under BBC emulation on the Archimedes, View Professional—the final iteration of the View suite on Acorn's 8-bit computers—had been advertised as a future product in June 1987 for November availability.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] View Professional, like the View series, had been developed for Acorn by Mark Colton, and his company—Colton Software—delivered the successor to this product as PipeDream for the Cambridge Computer Z88.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Another element of Acorn's early marketing strategy for the Archimedes was to emphasise the PC Emulator product which was a software-based emulator for IBM PC-compatible systems based on the 8088 processor running "legal MS-DOS programs".
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Alongside this, plans were also made for the launch of a podule (peripheral module) hardware expansion providing its own 80186 processor, a disk controller and connector for a disk drive.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] The emulator was described as having "very few compatibility problems" and was reported by diagnostic utilities as providing an 80188-based system, but the performance of the emulated system was regarded as slow.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Acorn reportedly acknowledged this by indicating the imminent availability of "an 80186 co-processor".
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Commentators were disappointed with the incoherent user interface provided by the software platform, with "Logistix looking like a PC, First Word slavishly copying GEM" and "101 other 'user interfaces'" amongst the early offerings.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] The result was the lack of a "personality" for the machine which risked becoming a system that would "never look as easy or as slick as the Mac".
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Computer Concepts, having begun development of various new applications for the Archimedes, was sufficiently frustrated with Arthur and its lack of "true multi-tasking" that it announced a rival operating system, Impulse, intended to host those applications on the machine.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Remedying various criticisms of the early operating environment, Acorn previewed RISC OS (or, more formally, RISC OS 2) in late 1988 and announced availability for April 1989.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] For a modest upgrade cost of £29, users received four ROM chips, three discs including several applications, and documentation.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] A common printing framework was introduced, with dot-matrix and PostScript printer drivers supplied, with such drivers available for use by all desktop applications.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] With RISC OS available, Acorn launched new and updated applications to take advantage of the improved desktop environment.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] First Word Plus was also updated to support the new RISC OS desktop environment, albeit retaining its own printer drivers, being positioned as complementing Acorn Desktop Publisher whose emphasis was on page layout as opposed to textual document creation.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] As part of an effort to grow the company's share of the home market, Acorn introduced a bundle called The Learning Curve, initially featuring the A3000, optional monitor and a set of applications (First Word Plus, the PC Emulator, and Genesis).
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] This bundle was enhanced later in 1990 to attract buyers to the A420/1, adding Acorn Desktop Publisher and some additional Genesis applications.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Acorn's document processing applications also began to see broader competition around this time, with Impression from Computer Concepts and Ovation from Beebug also providing competitive solutions for desktop publishing.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Also in 1990, PipeDream 3 became the first version of the PipeDream integrated suite, descended from Acorn's View Professional but developed and marketed by Colton Software, to be made available for the RISC OS desktop.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] The launch of the A5000 in late 1991 brought a new version of RISC OS to the market: RISC OS 3.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Providing the bundled applications and other resources in ROM saved an estimated 150 KB of workspace, thus being beneficial to users of 1 MB machines.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] The bundled RISC OS 3 applications were enhanced from their RISC OS 2 versions in various general ways, such as the introduction of keyboard shortcuts, but also with new, specific features.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] The printing system was also updated to support multiple printers at once, but in this first version of RISC OS 3 background printing was still not supported.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Edit gained improved formatting and searching support plus transparent BASIC program editing facilities.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] One somewhat visually obvious improvement delivered in RISC OS 3 was the use of "3D window borders" or, more accurately, dedicated bitmaps for window furniture, allowing different desktop styling effects.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] The appearance of the desktop would eventually shift towards Acorn's "NewLook" desktop theme, previewed in late 1993.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Various bugs in RISC OS 3.0 were fixed and various other improvements made, making it a worthwhile upgrade for A5000 users.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Notably, support for background printing was introduced.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] VAT-inclusive introductory pricing for the upgrade was £19 for RISC OS 3.0 users and £49 for RISC OS 2.0 users, with the upgrade package including ROMs, support discs and manuals.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] The non-introductory price of the upgrade was stated as being £89.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Problems with the storage management and filing systems were also identified.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] In 1994, the FileCore functionality in RISC OS was still limited to accessing 512 MB of any hard drive, with this being barely larger than the largest supplied Risc PC hard drive at the time.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Filing system limitations were also increasingly archaic: 77 files per directory and 10-character filenames, in contrast to more generous constraints imposed by the then-"imminent" Windows 95 and then-current Macintosh System 7 release.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] In the context of such a relationship, the possibility was raised of "bolting a RISC OS 'personality' on top of a low level IBM-developed operating system" to address RISC OS's deficiencies and to support virtual memory and long filenames.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] At this time, IBM was pursuing its Workplace OS strategy which emphasised a common operating system foundation supporting different system personalities.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] In mid-1991, the PC Emulator was eventually updated to work as a multitasking application on the RISC OS desktop, requiring 2 MB of RAM to do so, and supporting access to DOS files from the RISC OS desktop filer interface.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] The emulator itself permitted access to CD-ROM devices and ran MS-DOS 3.3 with a special mouse driver to permit the host machine's mouse to behave like a Microsoft bus mouse.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] CGA, EGA, MDA and partial VGA graphics support was implemented, and the emulated system could run Windows 3.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] The product cost £99, with an upgrade costing £29 for users of previous versions.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] An ARM3 processor was considered essential for "a workable turn of speed", this giving performance comparable with a 4.77 MHz 8086 PC-XT system.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Regarded as a "programming wonder", the PC Emulator was nevertheless regarded as being "too slow for intensive PC use".
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Shortly after the introduction of the updated PC Emulator, a hardware PC compatibility solution was announced by Aleph One, offering a 20 MHz 80386SX processor and VGA display capability, effectively delivering Acorn's envisaged PC podule in updated form.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] A low-cost alternative to Acorn's PC Emulator called FasterPC became available in 1993, priced at around £20 but with DOS not included (to be provided by the user at an estimated additional cost of £50).
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] The software provided PC emulation outside the desktop environment, with considerable performance benefits claimed relative to Acorn's product.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Regarded as being "considerably faster than the Acorn emulator when displaying graphics", with a two-times speed improvement observed for various tested programs, the product was considered appropriate for gaming, albeit at lower than VGA resolution.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] It was also unable to run Windows 3.1: the Aleph One PC expansion cards being the only solutions able to do so at that time.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Having considerably improved graphical capabilities compared to those provided with Acorn's 8-bit machines, a number of art packages were released for the Archimedes to exploit this particular area of opportunity, albeit rather cautiously at first.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] One of the first available packages, Clares' Artisan, supported image editing at the high resolution of 640 x 256 but only in the 16-colour mode 12, despite the availability of the 256-colour mode 15 as standard.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Favourably received as being "streets ahead" of art software on the BBC Micro, it was considered as barely the start of any real exploitation of the machine's potential.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Typical of software of the era, only months after the launch of the machine, Artisan provided its own graphical interface and, continuing the tradition of BBC Micro software, took over the machine entirely even to the point of editing the machine configuration and restoring it upon exiting.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Clares released a successor, Artisan 2, two years later to provide compatibility with RISC OS, replacing special-purpose printer support with use of the system's printer drivers, but not making the software a desktop application.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] The program's user interface deficiencies were regarded as less forgivable with the availability of a common desktop interface that would have addressed such problems and made the program "easier to use and a more powerful program as a result".
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Although regarded as powerful, the pricing was considered rather high from the perspective of those more familiar with the 8-bit software market, and the user interface was regarded as "only just bearable".
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Competitors to ProArtisan during 1989 included Art Nouveau from Computer Assisted Learning and Atelier from Minerva.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Both of these programs, like ProArtisan, ran in full-screen mode outside the desktop, used the 256-colour mode 15, and offered their own interfaces.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Atelier, however, was able to multi-task, providing the ability to switch back to the desktop and find applications still running and accessible.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Unlike other contemporary art programs, it also took advantage of the system's own anti-aliased fonts.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] One unusual feature was the ability to wrap areas of the canvas around solid objects.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Both programs also offered similar path editing facilities to ProArtisan, with it being noted that Art Nouveau's limitations in this regard might be remedied by using the support already present in RISC OS and provided by the Draw application functionality, as ProArtisan 2 eventually demonstrated.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] In 1989, RISC OS was provided with the Paint application on one of the accompanying application discs.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Despite a trend of gradual adoption of desktop functionality, in 1990, Arcol from ExpLAN offered a single-tasking, full-screen, 256-colour editing experience using the lower resolution 320 x 256 mode 13, supporting only bitmap fonts.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Aimed at educational users, its strengths apparently included real-time transformation of canvas areas, rapid zooming, and the absence of limitations on tools when zooming: arguably demonstrating more a limitation of contemporary packages with their own peculiar interfaces.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Apart from observations of limited functionality in some areas, one significant limitation reminiscent of earlier products was the inability to change display mode without affecting the picture being edited.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] This limitation was not convincingly removed in the second version, sold as Revelation 2 around a year later, with colours being redefined when selecting a 16-colour display mode while editing a 256-colour image, preserving the inability to edit 256-colour images in 16-colour modes.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] A further version update was delivered as the Revelation ImagePro product, being considered "the best art package that I have used on the Archimedes" by Acorn User's graphics columnist in late 1992.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] The path editing tools familiar from its predecessor were supported using functionality from Acorn's Draw application, and the image enhancement capabilities had also "undergone a major revamp".
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] At a reduced price of £135, and with use of the RISC OS desktop contributing to overall ease of use, the package was considered by one reviewer as "the best art package around at the moment for the Archimedes".
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Late in the Archimedes era, this being prior to the release of the Risc PC, a consensus amongst some reviewers formed in recommending Revelation ImagePro and ProArtisan 2 as the most capable bitmap-based art packages on the platform, with Arcol Desktop and First Paint also being reviewer favourites.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] With the release of the Risc PC and A7000, offering improved hardware capabilities and built-in support for 24-bit colour, the art package market changed significantly.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] However, the platform and hardware requirements of such packages were generally beyond Archimedes era machines, demanding 8 MB of RAM or 24-bit colour display modes (using 2 MB of dedicated video RAM) in some cases.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] A notable exception was Studio24 which, having been significantly updated in its second version, was reportedly "completely compatible" with the earlier machines.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] RISC OS was supplied with the Draw application, offering a range of tools for creating diagrams and pictures using vector graphics primitives, also permitting the incorporation of bitmap images and text into documents, and managing the different elements of documents as a hierarchy of objects.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] A significant capability provided by the application (and exploited by art packages) was that of Bézier curve editing, allowing shapes with smooth curves to be created, rendered and printed.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] The file format used by Draw was documented and extensible, and a range of tools emerged to manipulate Draw files for such purposes as distorting or transforming images or objects within images.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Amongst them was the Draw+ (or DrawPlus) application which defined other object types and also added other editing features, such as support for multiple levels or layers in documents.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] DrawPlus became available in 1991 and was released "at nominal cost" via public domain and shareware channels.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] The author of DrawPlus, Jonathan Marten, subsequently developed an application called Vector, released by an educational software publisher, 4Mation, in early 1992.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Priced at £100, even for site-wide usage, the software was considered "ideal... for technical drawing, to graphic design and even limited desktop publishing".
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] A version of Draw was also developed for Microsoft Windows by Oak Solutions.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] A significant introduction to the Archimedes' software portfolio came with the release of ArtWorks by Computer Concepts in late 1992.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Described in one preview as "perhaps the easiest to use, but most advanced graphic illustration package, on any personal computer today", ArtWorks provided an object-based editing paradigm reminiscent of Draw, refining the user interface, and augmenting the basic functionality with additional tools.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] A notable improvement over Draw was the introduction of graduated fills, permitting smooth gradients of colour within shapes, employing dithering to simulate a larger colour palette.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] The image rendering engine was also a distinguishing feature, offering different levels of rendering detail, with the highest level introducing anti-aliasing for individual lines.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Aimed at professional use, and complementing its sibling product, the Impression desktop publishing application, 24-bit colour depths and different colour models were supported.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] A key selling point of the package was its rendering speed, with it being reported that redraw speeds were up to five times faster in ArtWorks on an ARM3-based machine than those experienced with CorelDRAW running on a 486-based IBM PC-compatible system.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] ArtWorks would have broader significance as predecessor to the Xara Studio application and subsequent Windows-based products.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Alongside Acorn Desktop Publisher, Computer Concepts' "document processor" Impression and Beebug's Ovation provided a small selection of solutions in the realm of desktop publishing.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Acorn pursued the publishing industry with software and hardware system bundles, with Impression typically featuring prominently, even in the era of the Archimedes' successor, the Risc PC.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Ovation was eventually succeeded by Ovation Pro in 1996, offering stronger competition to Impression Publisher—itself the professional package in the range that had developed from Impression—and to industry-favoured applications such as QuarkXPress.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Amongst a variety of word processor applications, one enduring product family for the platform was developed by Icon Technology who had already released a word processor, MacAuthor, for the Apple Macintosh.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] This existing product was ported to RISC OS and released as EasiWriter in 1991, fully supporting the outline fonts and printing architecture of the host system.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Icon followed up to EasiWriter with an enhanced version ("EasiWriter's big brother") in 1992, TechWriter, featuring mathematical formula editing.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Upgraded "Professional" editions of EasiWriter and TechWriter were released in 1995, with the latter adding the notable feature of being able to save documents in TeX format.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Given the platform's presence in education, various educational word processing and publishing applications were available.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Longman Logotron supplied a "cost-effective introduction to DTP" in the form of FirstPage, retailing at £49 plus VAT with "unlimited" educational site licences costing up to £190.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Document layout capabilities were nevertheless available, supporting multiple column layouts, as were the traditional features such as spellchecking and integrated help absent from FirstPage.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Pricing was even more competitive at around £30, or £40 with spellchecking support.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Aside from the hybrid word processor and spreadsheet application, PipeDream, being released in versions 3 and 4 for the RISC OS desktop environment, Colton Software released a standalone word processor, Wordz, in 1993, with plans for companion applications and a degree of integration between them.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] PipeDream itself was later updated to version 4.5, conforming more closely to the RISC OS look and feel, being initially offered as an upgrade for users of version 4.0.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Acorn's own interest in developing applications led it to initiate work on the Schema spreadsheet application, only to disengage from application development and to transfer the product to Clares who, with assistance from the originally commissioned developers, brought the product to market.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Despite its origins as one component in an application suite that was never delivered as envisaged, a cut-down version of Schema 2 was later incorporated into Acorn's Advance application suite alongside variants of Computer Concepts' Impression Junior and Iota Software's DataPower.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Schema 2 itself was enhanced with a "powerful macro language" and released in 1994.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] In the spreadsheet category, Longman Logotron's Eureka, released in 1992, provided robust competition to Schema and PipeDream, seeking to emulate Microsoft Excel in terms of functionality and user interface conventions.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] The interoperability benefits of the updated product, Eureka 2, were later given as a reason for Acorn to adopt the software internally, acquiring a 300-user site licence and thus allowing its employees to convert "substantial spreadsheet data which needed converting from Lotus 1-2-3".
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Some analysis and graphing capabilities were also provided.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] A version of PinPoint would eventually be made available for Windows, ostensibly aimed at market research as opposed to education, as its producer attempted to broaden its audience and availability for different platforms.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Also emphasising a desktop publishing style of presentation was Iota Software's DataPower, employing these facilities to customise record entry to "make data collection as much like form-filling as possible" and in the reporting functionality of the software.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] In 1993, Longman Logotron introduced S-Base, a programmable database offering the possibility of customised database application development.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Described as "a more disciplined, less graphical approach to database design", the software enforced a degree of discipline around data type and table definition, but it also retained various graphical techniques to design forms for interaction with the database.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Building on such foundations, programs could be written in a language called S to handle user interaction, graphical user interface events, and to interact with data in the database.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Being compared to the contemporary DOS-based Paradox software, it was regarded as having more of an emphasis on "database applications" than actual databases, also being considered as similar to the contemporary RISC OS application, Archway, as a kind of "application generator" tool.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Despite spreadsheet and database applications offering graphing capabilities, dedicated applications were also available to produce a wider range of graphs and charts.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Amongst these were Chartwell from Risc Developments and the Graphbox and Graphbox Professional packages from Minerva Software.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] With the introduction of CD-ROM and the broader adoption of multimedia, Acorn announced a full-motion video system called Acorn Replay in early 1992, supporting simultaneous audio and video at up to 25 frames per second in the RISC OS desktop or in "a low resolution full screen mode".
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Unlike certain other full-motion video technologies, Replay offered the ability to read compressed video data from mass storage in real time and to maintain a constant frame rate, all on standard computing hardware without the need for dedicated video decoding hardware.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] The compression techniques employed by Replay reportedly offered "compression factors of between 25 and 40" on the source video data, with the software decompression requiring a computer with 2 MB of RAM or more.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Given a slower access medium such as CD-ROM or floppy disk, video could be played back at up to 12.5 frames per second, with up to 25 frames per second from a hard disk.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] One 800 KB floppy disk could reportedly hold 12 seconds of video.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Acorn's introduction of Replay prompted comparisons with Apple's QuickTime system which was already broadly available to users of Macintosh systems.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Replay's advantages included the efficiency of the solution on existing hardware, with even an entry-level A3000 upgraded to 2 MB of RAM being able to handle 2 MB of data per second to achieve the advertised 12.5 frames per second playback.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] QuickTime was also reported as only able to play video smoothly at 1/16th of the size of the screen, also favouring 32,000 colour display modes that were available on Macintosh systems with 68020 or faster processors.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] One disadvantage of Replay on the Acorn systems was the limitation of playback to 256 colours imposed by the built-in video system.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Educational software and resources providers saw the potential of Replay to deliver interactive video at a more affordable price than existing Laservision content, although it was noted that, at that time, Laservision still provided "the best quality, full-screen, moving image to date".
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Educators also looked forward to more accessible authoring possibilities, with children being able to record, edit and incorporate their own video into their projects.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Indications that this situation would change were present in the QuickTime market, with it already supporting the creation of short movies in conjunction with video digitiser cards and editing tools such as Adobe Premiere.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Support for video authoring on the desktop emerged in 1993 with the Replay DIY product from Irlam Instruments: a single-width podule suitable for A540 and A5000 computers with 2 MB of RAM or more, these being the only models available at the time with the necessary performance.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] The podule accepted analogue video input from video cameras, recorders and laserdisc players, allowing the video to be previewed in a window on the desktop.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] While recording, no preview would be shown, and the hardware would digitise the audio and video input, transfer the data to the computer's memory, and this would then be sent straight to a hard disk.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] At its introduction, the video quality was limited to "normal Arm2 Replay, that is 256-colour, 160x128 pixels at 12.5 frames per second", although an upgrade to capture 25 frames per second was anticipated.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Uncompressed video occupied around 21 MB per minute, but processing of such video using the provided Acorn Replay compression software would bring the size of the resulting video down to around 4 or 5 MB per minute.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Compression was, however, relatively slow, since the compression scheme was asymmetric, meaning that decompression was fast enough to facilitate playback in real time, but compression could take "a few minutes for every few seconds of video".
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] To support the more convenient offline editing environment, a highly efficient symmetric compression scheme known as ESCaPE (Eidos Software Compression and Playback Engine) had been devised, offering movie sizes of around 1.5 MB per minute.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] In 1995, Computer Concepts offered a bundle featuring Eidoscope and the company's Eagle M2 "multimedia card" which featured audio and video capture, improved audio playback, and MIDI ports.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Aimed at non-professional applications, Eidoscope was limited to editing movies up to a resolution of 160 x 128 and did not support time codes.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] With the introduction of the Archimedes, Acorn continued the practice established for its earlier machines of offering languages in addition to BASIC, albeit priced somewhat higher than the earlier implementations, these including Pascal, C, Prolog, Fortran and Lisp.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Other vendors produced implementations of Forth, such as Silicon Vision's RiscForth, and Logo, such as Logotron Logo.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Other Acornsoft languages such as BCPL and COMAL were not ported to the new platform and had to be run under emulation.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] A Smalltalk-80 implementation was also made available by Smalltalk Express costing £620, offering the familiar window-based environment, but requiring a 4 MB machine and a hard drive.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Acorn had always emphasised its implementation of BBC BASIC in its earlier machines, and the Archimedes was delivered with an enhanced version, BASIC V, that provided additional control-flow structures such as while loops, case statements, and multi-line if statements.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Graphics primitives and operations were also accessible via special-case keywords such as `ELLIPSE`, `CIRCLE`, `RECTANGLE` and `FILL`, and the specification of colours was extended to access the broader colour palette supported by the hardware.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Various commands were also added for sprite plotting and manipulation and to enable, confine, disable and read the position and state of the mouse pointer.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Assembly language support was included, as it had been in the BASIC provided by Acorn's 8-bit models, with the language updated to describe instructions for the ARM processor instead of the 6502 (or other processor families) familiar from the earlier machines.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Access to operating system functionality was provided from BASIC, with some of the demonstration programs provided with the Arthur operating system employing the font and window manager operating system modules, including the rudimentary desktop environment.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] The arrival of RISC OS brought the possibility of developing desktop, or WIMP, applications in BASIC and other languages.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] To ease the development of such applications, various products offering toolkits or libraries were announced, one of the earliest being Archway, this providing tools to define different aspects of an application, including window layout design and menu editing, along with BASIC library routines.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] More ambitious attempts were later made to extend BASIC to access desktop functionality.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] For instance, HelixBasic added extra keywords to BASIC V whilst also making it possible for traditional BASIC programs, including graphical programs, to run in the window-based environment transparently and concurrently.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Although the performance of the supplied BASIC interpreter had been regarded as competitive, various BASIC compilers were produced for the system, such as Dabs Press' Archimedes Basic Compiler (ABC) and Silicon Vision's RiscBASIC.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Both products focused on improving the performance of the input programs, but Silicon Vision subsequently introduced a separate product, WimpGEN, as an accessory for desktop application developers.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] This product provided window and menu editors that would generate BASIC source code implementing the functionality required to support operation in the desktop environment.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Specific application functionality would then be added, and the resulting program could also be compiled using RiscBASIC before being run.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] BBC BASIC on the Archimedes was considered as a vehicle for cross-platform game development by David Braben and other developers before the Archimedes was released, Braben being the author of the three-dimensional Lander game supplied with the machine.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] The ability to cross-assemble code in the BASIC assembler for processors other than the ARM was devised, and support from key individuals at Acorn was secured, but the company's management were reluctant to incorporate support for other systems in its product, thus curtailing the effort.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] That Acorn had been in a position to offer its own C compiler was reportedly the consequence of "a stroke of luck": this product having been originally developed by Arthur Norman and Alan Mycroft for a mainframe at Cambridge University and subsequently offered to Acorn.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Acorn's original C compiler and assembler products were superseded by its Desktop C and Desktop Assembler products in mid-1991.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] These products comprised Acorn's Desktop Development Environment, aiming to reduce the time and effort involved in developing applications and modules along with supporting such activities in the desktop environment itself.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Both products provided an enhanced version of Edit known as SrcEdit for source code editing that supported "throwback": navigation to locations in source code produced by other tools such as the C compiler.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Alongside compiler, assembler and linker tools, a build utility known as Make and supporting Makefiles was provided along with an improved version of the FormEd tool used for application window design.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Desktop C cost £229 plus VAT, and Desktop Assembler cost £149 plus VAT.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Acorn's C++ strategy was the subject of a degree of criticism.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Initially, the company announced the availability of AT&T's CFront to its registered developer community, this translating C++ code for further compilation by Acorn's Desktop C product.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Acorn followed up by offering a new product, replacing Desktop C, that integrated CFront 3.0 to support C and C++ compilation, albeit without support for exceptions.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Feedback from developers had been negative, however, citing poor-quality code and slow compilation times, with developers apparently wanting "a true native C++ compiler with good RISC OS environment support".
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Despite the adoption of C++ class libraries on other platforms, Acorn chose to provide user interface component functionality using a collection of modules, known as the Toolbox, accessible at the system call level instead.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Apart from a port of the GNU C++ compiler, itself requiring at least 4 MB of RAM to run, the only significant competition to Acorn's C and C++ products were the Easy C and Easy C++ products from Beebug, with the former being announced in late 1993 as a Risc Developments product costing £49 plus VAT.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Priced significantly less than Acorn's compiler, Easy C provided a narrower range of tools, lacking the debugger of Acorn's product in particular, and had also not been validated as conforming to the ANSI language standard, unlike Acorn's compiler.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Nevertheless, it did provide the essential compiler, assembler, linker and build tools, aiming to be "an easy to use C development system aimed at the lower end of the market".
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] In late 1994, Beebug followed up by announcing Easy C++ in advance of the availability of Acorn's own C++ product.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Easy C++ compiled C++ source code directly to ARM object code and supported both templates and exceptions.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] It was priced at £99 plus VAT or £49 plus VAT as an upgrade from Easy C.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] The product was seemingly positively received, with the developers having "achieved the target they set themselves" by delivering a native C++ compiler, although the lack of updated documentation and the need for further development to improve the product were also identified.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Ultimately, the stated lack of a suitable C++ compiler and accompanying class libraries for the platform led prominent development houses to focus on products for other platforms and to abandon plans to release new software for RISC OS.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Charles Moir of Computer Concepts justified the development of Xara Studio, a graphics application described as effectively "ArtWorks for the PC", indicating that only the larger market for Windows software could make the necessary investment in such a sophisticated application worthwhile.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Since Windows development could leverage C++ and platform-specific class libraries, Computer Concepts had expected Acorn to deliver comparable tools and resources to make the development of such software possible on the Acorn platform "to no avail".
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] Ben Finn of Sibelius Software indicated that Sibelius 7 had been a "completely new piece of software" written in C++, in contrast to earlier versions written in assembly language, primarily due to the difficulties of implementing requested features in such a low-level language.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] The portability of C++ software also permitted Sibelius to be made available for the PC and Mac platforms.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] However, with Acorn unable to provide a suitably updated C++ development suite, the company was unable to deliver its new product on RISC OS.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p02] There are **400** commercial games for Acorn Archimedes.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] Since the video controller would not support display modes smaller than 20 KB, the lowest resolution modes were supported in the operating system by employing modes with twice the horizontal resolution and duplicating horizontally adjacent pixels.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] The A540 (and corresponding R-series workstations) offered three BNC sockets, adding one for a separate horizontal sync connection for certain monitors.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] Acorn suggested the 19-inch Taxan Viking and Philips M19P114 monitors, with the former being offered in a bundle with the R140 workstation.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] The Taxan Viking R140 product bundled the existing Viking product with appropriate cabling and produced a "rock steady" 66 Hz mode 23 display, albeit with mouse pointer corruption at the extreme right of the screen due to "a bug in the VIDC chip".
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] The A5000 unlike its predecessor, the A540, did not support high resolution monochrome modes.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] An expansion to speed up the VIDC chip in the Archimedes from 24 MHz to 36 MHz was announced by Atomwide in 1990, offering higher resolution display modes for machines connected to multisync monitors.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] Although resolutions up to 1280 x 480 and 1024 x 640 were supported, flicker due to a decreased refresh rate was reported as a problem, with 1152 x 486 appearing to be more comfortable in this regard.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] The SVGA resolution of 800 x 600 was also supported in up to 16 colours.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] One side-effect of increasing the frequency of the VIDC was to also increase the frequency of generated sounds, since the VIDC was also responsible for sound generation.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] VIDC enhancers were supplied by some monitor vendors together with the appropriate cable for Archimedes machines, although fitting the device still required approved service work to be performed.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] Monitors such as the Taxan 795 Multivision were only usable in multisync modes without the VIDC enhancer whose accompanying software sought to "redefine all modes" to be compatible with the display as well as providing new modes.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] One drawback of VIDC enhancer solutions was the increased memory bandwidth used by the VIDC at its newly elevated frequency, slowing down machines when using higher resolution modes, particularly machines with ARM2 processors and slower memory busses.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] However, such cards were also able to support more flexible palettes in 256 colour modes than the VIDC, and for lower resolutions, greater colour depths offering over 32,000 colours could be supported.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] The ColourCard was reported to allow an ARM2 system to use a 1600 x 600 display mode with 16 colours (occupying 480 KB) with an operating speed of "160% of the speed of the considerably lower resolution Acorn mode 28", this being 640 x 480 with 256 colours (occupying 300 KB).
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] Subsequent developments from State Machine brought the G16 card, offering application-specific support for 15 and 16 bits per pixel modes.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] Alongside bandwidth constraints, a fundamental limitation to the size of VIDC framebuffers was imposed by the memory controller, limiting the size of framebuffers transferred to the VIDC through DMA to a specific 512 KB physical memory region.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] State Machine's ColourBurst card, announced together with its G16 card, employed memory mapping techniques to provide 1 MB of video RAM instead of the 512 KB of earlier cards and thus supporting larger screen modes.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] The ColourBurst was, when reviewed in late 1993, the first 24-bit colour card available for the Archimedes, also supporting various upgrades including the "video switch" capability absent from earlier cards, PAL encoding, and other professional capabilities.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] Coincidentally, ARM Limited announced the VIDC20—the successor to the VIDC10 in the Archimedes—at around the same time as the introduction of the Computer Concepts and State Machine product ranges in late 1992.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] In late 1993, Computer Concepts announced the ColourCard Gold, developed in conjunction with Acorn to offer 15 bits per pixel support in the desktop environment.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] Meanwhile, State Machine announced the ClusterCard for 33 MHz A5000 models, plugging into the memory controller socket and supporting upgrades to 8 MB of RAM alongside graphics enhancements offering 1 MB or 2 MB of video RAM.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] The ClusterCard, employing the G335 Cluster Module was reported to be the first graphics card for the Archimedes series not requiring the use of the VIDC.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] The full version of the card was reportedly available for A300 series, A400 series, A5000 and A540 machines.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] Somewhat distinct from general graphics enhancements, various products were also introduced to support the broadcasting industry and other professional imaging applications.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] In late 1990, Millipede Electronic Graphics announced an imaging product called APEX (Archimedes P3 Expansion) featuring "four P3 (pixel pipeline processor) chips, together with an Arm3 processor running at 27 MHz".
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] With support for "broadcast quality graphics at 32 bits per pixel", hardware support for windows and sprites, emphasising real-time image combination and manipulation, the product was aimed at professional users and priced accordingly, with the version providing 4 MB of RAM projected to cost £2750.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] Nevertheless, a licensing agreement had been reached with Acorn to "enable Risc OS graphics functions to be fully emulated".
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] Following up from this earlier product, Millipede offered an "all new Apex Imager" video card in early 1994 featuring the four custom chips, ARM3, FPA, and 16 MB of video RAM on a double-width podule costing £3975, this being virtually unchanged from the pricing of the original product from 1990.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] This product appears to make extensive use of FPGA devices and offers numerous video input and output facilities.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] Previous Eidos capture solutions used A540 machines with 8 MB of RAM.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] The Archimedes was capable of producing eight-channel, 8-bit, stereo sound, with the video controller chip being responsible for sound generation, it having direct memory access capabilities to independently stream audio data to the output circuitry.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] Some users sought to bypass the audio filtering circuitry to improve sound from the external audio connector.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] The Archimedes did not provide hardware support for floating-point arithmetic as standard, but the system was designed so that one might be added, with a floating-point co-processor instruction set architecture having been defined by Acorn for programs to use.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] As part of the system architecture, a software module provides an emulation of such a co-processor, handling floating-point instructions unsupported in hardware using software written using conventional ARM instructions.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] In the first generation of Archimedes 300 and 400 series machines, only the 400 series had the appropriate expansion capability to add a floating-point unit (FPU) or co-processor, although the emulator was supported on all models.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] The expansion capability was retained in the 400/1 series.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] The FPU expansion card was delivered for the R140 workstation and 400 series in 1989, priced at £599 plus VAT, and was based on the WE32206, with a "protocol converter chip" being used to translate between the ARM and the WE32206.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] The WE32206 card was also offered for Acorn's Springboard expansion card for IBM PC compatibles.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] Somewhat more applied testing demonstrated speed-ups for benchmark programs of up to eight times, aligning with Acorn's claims, but contrasted these gains with the broader performance increases attainable from an ARM3 upgrade, these offering a more general four-fold speed improvement.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] Largely focusing on BASIC programming, one reviewer concluded that the FPU was "all but obsolete" with the availability of the ARM3 upgrade.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] Another conceded that some but not all C programs would benefit from the FPU since "a good programmer will avoid using floating point instructions if at all possible", suggesting that Acorn's R140 workstation would benefit more from the upgrade.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] The Archimedes models based on the ARM3 processor supported a completely new "arithmetic co-processor" or "floating-point accelerator" known as the FPA.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] Released in 1993 for the R260 workstation and the A540 and A5000 machines, priced at £99 plus VAT, the FPA device—known specifically as the FPA10—was fitted in a dedicated socket on the processor card for the R260 and A540, or in a motherboard socket in the A5000.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] It offered a peak throughput of 5 MFLOPS at 26 MHz.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] The models officially supporting the FPA had been introduced some time prior to availability of the device, and various ARM3 upgrade cards for earlier models had also been made available with an FPA socket in anticipation of eventual availability.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] Fabrication of the device was performed by GEC Plessey Semiconductors and was reported to be in "an advanced stage of production" in early 1993.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] Further details were given upon the eventual release of the FPA10, stating a 26 MHz operating frequency and a power consumption of 250 mW.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] Other programs such as Draw and ArtWorks—a Computer Concepts product—used their own arithmetic routines instead of the floating-point emulator (FPE) and, as anticipated, were therefore unable to take advantage of the accelerated floating-point instructions.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] However, various free of charge or low-cost programs ported from other systems, such as POV-Ray, plus selected native applications such as Clares' Illusionist and Oak Solutions' WorraCAD, did exhibit substantial performance gains from the FPA with speed-ups of between five and ten times.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] Programs compiled by Intelligent Interfaces' Fortran compiler were reported as running "some routines up to 20 times faster with the FPA10".
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] Speculative execution was also employed to improve performance.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] Observed BASIC program performance remained in line with experiences from the earlier FPU solution.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] Another analysis employing benchmarks of individual arithmetic and trigonometric operations indicated a more uniform distribution of performance improvements for BASIC VI programs, also noting that BASIC VI delivered more precision than BASIC V in its floating-point representation.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] ARM3 upgrades were also produced with 33 MHz ARM3 processors, but unlike their 25 MHz counterparts which were available with FPA10 co-processors already fitted, these faster cards were not supplied with FPA11 co-processors, perhaps due to availability issues with the faster part.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] In early 1990, Aleph One introduced an upgrade board for Archimedes A300 and A400 series models featuring the ARM3 processor which had been designed by Acorn but was sold independently by VLSI Technology.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] Although the ARM2 employed by current models could reportedly be run at 20 MHz, it was only ever run at 8 MHz due to external limitations, these being the speed of the data bus and of the "relatively slow", but correspondingly relatively inexpensive, RAM devices in use.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] The ARM3 incorporated a 4 KB on-chip combined instruction and data cache, loosening such external constraints and thus permitting the processor to be run productively at the elevated 20 MHz frequency.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] Original A300 and A400 series models, as opposed to the A400/1 series, required an upgrade to MEMC1a.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] The upgrade was introduced at a price of £684.24, with the MEMC1a costing £57.50 for those users who needed it.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] By the end of 1991, an ARM3 upgrade had been offered for the A3000 by Aleph One in association with Atomwide and by Watford Electronics.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] Since the ARM2 was soldered directly to the motherboard in the A3000 using surface mounting techniques, the upgrade had to be performed by a fitting service, and prices included courier collection, fitting, testing and return within five working days.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] With the A5000 having been launched with a 25 MHz ARM3 fitted, these A3000 upgrade boards carried a processor running at this higher frequency relative to earlier upgrades.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] Originally, the Aleph One product had been priced at £468.83, but the announcement of a board by Watford Electronics led to a reduced price of £392.45.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] The Watford product had an introductory price of £274.95.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] In late 1992, Simtec Electronics announced a board with an additional socket for the FPA device, thus allowing older machines to join the A540 and A5000 in potentially taking advantage of it.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] By this time, prices for ARM3 upgrades had been reduced to the point that this Simtec upgrade cost only £175 plus VAT.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] Competitors including IFEL and CJE Micros followed Simtec's lead and announced similar combined ARM3/FPA upgrades.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] In contrast, Aleph One stated that the FPA would "not be available for a long time yet", indicating the pursuit of "a better solution based on the newer Arm600 chip plus an FPA".
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] Other vendors had apparently ruled out similar ARM600-based products on the basis of cost.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] In 1993, IFEL later announced a 35 MHz ARM3 upgrade based on a limited quantity—approximately 1500—of available suitably rated parts, these having a ceramic package whose volume ruled out its use in machines with limited internal space, making the upgrade suitable for A300, A400 or R140 machines.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] A combined ARM3/FPA upgrade with the faster ARM3 was under consideration, although the lack of suitably rated FPA chips meant that a switch would be provided to manually change the clock frequency between 25 MHz and 35 MHz.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] A target price of £199 including VAT was estimated.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] Prior to the availability of the FPA, Simtec reduced the price of its combined ARM3/FPA board to £165 plus VAT.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] With the upgrade, performance of these machines was reported as increasing from 7 MIPS to 10 MIPS, this compared to almost 13 MIPS for a 25 MHz ARM3.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] By employing a 16 MHz clock signal, as envisaged by Acorn in the design of the A3010, in conjunction with dynamic RAM devices with a 70 ns access time, the upgrade provided a total of 4 MB of RAM and a 40 percent performance improvement.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] Unlike standard RAM upgrades, the turbo upgrade needed to be fitted at a suitable facility, and the board was priced slightly higher than a standard RAM upgrade at £129 plus VAT.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] A "super turbo" version of the board with 20 MHz crystal and 45 ns dynamic RAM devices was reviewed and apparently available subject to component availability, reportedly achieving 12.25 MIPS.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] Aleph One, having founded the ARM3 upgrade industry, found that increased competition from "six or eight companies making Arm3 upgrades" drove down prices to the point that "margins fell, and the bottom fell out of the Arm3 market".
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] However, revenues from ARM3 upgrades allowed Aleph One to pursue the development of IBM PC-compatible podule expansions and eventually the PC processor card for the Risc PC, these having "a higher intellectual content than Arm3 upgrades" and being more difficult for potential competitors to make.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] Plans were indicated to develop a PowerPC processor card for the Risc PC.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] Neither the PowerPC upgrade for the Risc PC nor the earlier ARM600-based upgrade for the Archimedes series appeared, with Acorn itself abandoning plans to combine newer ARM600 or ARM700 parts with FPA devices to provide improved floating point performance.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] ARM3 upgrades were produced for several years, but with the ARM3 part being "officially discontinued" by its manufacturer VLSI in 1996, upgrade vendors such as IFEL were predicting scarcity and unable to guarantee further supplies of such products.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] Demand for such upgrades, even in 1996, was reported as "steady" with schools still upgrading "batches of old A300 and A400 machines".
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] Later still, in 1997, Simtec announced a "special batch" of ARM3 upgrades for A300 and A400 series machines and the A3000, featuring a socket for the 25 MHz FPA10 or 33 MHz FPA11, with the former being supplied already fitted for a total product cost of £199 plus VAT.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] Acorn initially planned to produce an IBM PC-compatible system on a podule (peripheral module), complete with 80186 processor (running at 10 MHz) and disk drive support.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] Subsequent pricing and competitiveness considerations led to the product being shelved.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] However, in late 1991, hardware supplier Aleph One announced a PC podule based on a 20 MHz Intel 80386SX processor with VGA display capability.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] Launched in early 1992, the podule fitted with 1 MB of RAM cost £595, whereas a 4 MB version cost £725.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] A socket on the board permitted the 80387 maths co-processor to be fitted for hardware floating point arithmetic support, this costing an extra £120.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] Integration of the PC system involved the Archimedes providing display, keyboard and disk support.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] In the initial version, the supplied 386PC application would put the Archimedes into dedicated display mode and thus take over the display, but subsequent versions promised operation of the PC in a window, much like the updated PC Emulator from the era.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] Screen memory requirements were around 256 KB for MDA and CGA, with EGA and VGA requiring another 256 KB.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] Separate serial and parallel ports were fitted on the expansion board due to limitations with the ports on existing Archimedes machines, but integration with those ports was also planned for subsequent versions of the product.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] This product was apparently never released, however, and its designers subsequently formed graphics expansion producer State Machine.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] In late 1992, Aleph One reduced the price of the 386-based card by £100, also upgrading the processor to a 25 MHz part, and introduced a card featuring a 25 MHz Cyrix 486SLC processor, with the new card retaining the maths co-processor option of the earlier product.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] The stated performance of this new card was approximately twice that of the 386-based card but only "40 percent of the performance of a standard 33 MHz 486DX PC clone".
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] However, upgraded Windows drivers reportedly allowed even the 386-based card to exceed the graphical performance of such a 486-based clone, effectively employing the host Archimedes as a kind of "Windows accelerator".
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] A subsequent review moderated such claims somewhat, indicating a Windows performance "not noticeably better than an average un-accelerated 386SX PC clone", although acceleration support was expected to improve, with device drivers for various direct drive laser printers also expected.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] The product was priced at £495 for the 1 MB version and £595 for the 4 MB version, with a future revision of the product anticipated that would support up to 16 MB of RAM.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] In 1993, Aleph One collaborated with Acorn to produce Acorn-branded versions of the PC cards for use with the A3020 and A4000 which used a distinct "mini-podule expansion system".
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] The 25 MHz 386SX and 486SLC cards were offered in this profile to provide DOS and Windows compatibility, branded as the PC386 and PC486, priced at £275 and £499 respectively.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] In late 1993, the supplied software was upgraded and discounts to the products announced, bringing the respective prices down to £225 and £425.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] Acorn also offered bundles of the A4000 with a hard drive and each of the cards.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] Coincidentally at this time, with speculation building about future Acorn computer products, Acorn's product marketing manager had been reported as suggesting that such products "would have an empty Intel socket for customers to add PC Dos and Windows compatibility".
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] Such remarks were clarified by Acorn's technical director, indicating that an Intel "second processor" was merely an option in an architecture supporting multiple processors.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] Ultimately, Acorn would release the Risc PC with dual processor capabilities and support for using a "low cost (£99 upwards) plug-in 486 PC processor or other CPUs" alongside an ARM processor.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] Redesigned PC cards were released in 1994, introducing the option of a faster 50 MHz 486SLC2 processor for a reported doubling of the performance over the fastest existing cards.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] Up to 16 MB of SIMM-profile RAM could be fitted, and a local hard drive controller was added.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] The supplied software was also upgraded to support Windows in a resolution of 800 x 600 at up to 16 colours, and optional network driver support was available to use the card as a Novell NetWare client and for Windows for Workgroups 3.11.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] Pricing remained similar to earlier models.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] Reported performance was better than the previous generation of cards but "still slow compared to all but the most basic of modern PCs, but certainly usable".
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] The Windows User benchmarks rated the performance as similar to a fast 386SX-based system or a "standard" 386DX-based system, with the faster processor yielding a more favourable rating, but with the hard drive and graphics tests bringing the overall rating down.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] A range of podules providing access to parallel processing capabilities using Inmos Transputer processors were announced by Gnome Computing in late 1989.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] Aside from a "Link Adaptor" podule for interfacing to external Transputer hardware, the "TRAM Motherboard" podule combined the Link Adaptor's interfacing logic with the hosting of up to four "TRAMs" (Transputer plus RAM modules), providing a complete development system based on the Archimedes.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] Also offered was a "Transputer Baseboard" podule featuring a T425 or T800 with up to 8 MB of RAM.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] A single podule with four TRAMs, each employing a T800 processor, was stated as giving 40 MIPS of performance, with a hypothetical 160 MIPS available on an Archimedes with four podule slots.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] Digital signal processing capabilities were provided by the Burden Neuroscience 56001 DSP Card, originally developed by the Burden Neurological Institute as in-house hardware for use in conjunction with Archimedes systems but marketed by The Serial Port.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] This card was fitted as a single-width podule but, unusually, needed manual configuration instead of identifying itself to the host computer.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] The podule itself offered a 32 MHz Motorola 56001 digital signal processor together with 192 KB of RAM, two 16-bit analogue-to-digital converters, two 16-bit digital-to-analogue converters, and serial communications capabilities.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] A 25-pin connector provided the means to interface the board to other hardware.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] An assembler was provided, although this reportedly required Acorn's Desktop Development Environment to function, and software was also provided to interact with the board, view memory and register contents, and to visualise memory ranges in real time.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] Described as appropriate for "high speed analogue data acquisition or output" supporting real time signal processing, the product was considered "a useful 56001 development test bed", requiring a certain level of expertise, but was also considered good value at a price of £449 plus VAT.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] CD-ROM technology was introduced to the Archimedes range in 1990 with the launch of Next Technology's CD-ROM solution for the A3000 and earlier Archimedes models.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] Combining an SCSI interface and CD-ROM drive and supplied with a sample disc for a total price of £995, the solution provided a filing system so that standard CD-ROM media could be browsed and read like any other kind of disc.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] An application was also provided to play audio tracks on CD Audio and mixed-format discs through the drive's headphone socket.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] The drive itself used a caddy to hold the discs inserted into the drive.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] One limitation experienced on RISC OS was with the content on various CD-ROM titles, this often being designed for MS-DOS and featuring DOS-only software to offer search and database-related functionality.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] Next Technology aimed to remedy this situation by offering a service to let users create their own CD-ROMs at around £300 per disc, leading to the initial conclusion that schools and institutional users would benefit from the format much more than home users.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] Two years on from the introduction of CD-ROM products, adoption of the technology was still at a "tentative state", with £8 million having been spent on equipment and an estimated 3,000 drives deployed in UK schools.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] Drive prices had fallen significantly, from around £1,000 to £300 and with a further decline to £200 anticipated.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] Acorn's video solution for its own computers was the Replay system, introducing compression formats and associated software for playback and authoring.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] Reservations about the read-only nature of CD-ROM discs was also seen as a "wounding flaw", leaving users to consider alternatives for convenient bulk storage, with magneto-optical drives emerging at this time.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] Nevertheless, CD-ROM adoption was seen as inevitable, particularly given the format's benefits for holding large amounts of text and making the searching of such text convenient, and with government initiatives having helped to make an estimated 100 titles available for both MS-DOS and RISC OS.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] Acorn would go on to announce Photo CD support in its products in early 1993, with operating system and application enhancements being delivered by the end of that year.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] Support for multi-session CD-ROMs entailed some upgrades to existing SCSI interfaces as well as the use of drives with the appropriate capabilities such as Acorn's own Multimedia Expansion Unit.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] The Archimedes was launched with provision for an optional Econet module to be installed, this module being the same as that used by the Master series.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] Acorn introduced Ethernet connectivity with the launch of the company's R140 Unix workstation, also offering expansion cards for Archimedes models.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] In 1992, Atomwide also introduced Ethernet cards for the traditional Archimedes expansion bus and for the internal expansion slot in the A3000.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] Ethernet could be used as faster medium for existing Econet-style networking, or the TCP/IP protocol stack could be employed instead.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] Acorn sought to introduce Econet functionality on top of Internet protocols with its Acorn Universal Networking (AUN) suite of technologies.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] Numerous vendors offered Ethernet expansion cards, such as Ant Limited (via Atomwide), Digital Services, i-cubed, Oak Solutions, and Risc Developments.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] Although compatible with AUN, some of the cards offered support for vendor-specific enhancements such as Oak Solutions' ClassNet and Digital Services' NetGain.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] Other networking approaches were available, including the sharing of hard drives using a SCSI bus, and emerging technologies such as Asynchronous Transfer Mode were deployed on the Acorn platform, notably in SJ Research's Nexus product.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] A ROM podule was also announced with the anticipation that users upgrading from the earlier machines would choose to fit their application and language ROMs in their new machine, these running under the 6502 emulator provided with the operating system.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] In early 1988, Computer Concepts announced its own ROM/RAM podule that was capable of accepting seven chips, each with a maximum capacity of 128 KB, supporting the use of installed RAM as "a RAM-disc filing system" with optional battery backup to retain the contents with the machine powered down.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] The company also announced the availability of its existing BBC Micro productivity suite for use with the board.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] Acorn also released its ROM and I/O podules in the first half of 1988.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] Other companies also offered I/O expansions, such as the Unilab I/O Box 3000 for the A3000 that provided three user ports, analogue port and 1 MHz bus port.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p04] HCCS and Morley Electronics supplied podules for the A3000 that provided user and analogue ports, with Morley's product also offering an I2C bus connector ostensibly for the use of subsequent peripherals from the company.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p05] Similar enthusiasm was reflected by the same writer in a *Byte* magazine preview of the A310 the following month.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p05] Acorn had predicted sales of 20,000 Archimedes machines by the end of 1987 and 120,000 by the end of 1988.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p05] However, by mid-1988 only 14,000 units had reportedly been sold.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p05] One commentator attributed such disappointing sales to the lack of software support for the system, noting that Acorn had not invested sufficiently in software availability and that few established companies in the Acorn market were delivering native applications.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p05] Acorn's strategy of commissioning applications available for other platforms, such as First Word Plus and Logistix, was regarded as "hardly innovative" and that the platform needed "a massive injection of native, innovative software", perhaps by a revitalised Acornsoft.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p05] The introduction of the A3000, launched with RISC OS fitted, delivered better than expected sales for Acorn, with an estimated total of 50,000 Archimedes and A3000 systems having been sold by the end of 1989.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p05] In this period, over two-thirds of computer sales into primary schools had been Acorn models, with Acorn's 40% share of sales into secondary schools making the company the largest single vendor in this section of the market.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p05] By mid-1992, a reported 180,000 Archimedes machines had been sold, again due to strong A3000 sales.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p05] By 1994 and the launch of the Risc PC, over 300,000 Archimedes machines had been sold, and the A3000 had become the fourth best selling computer in the United Kingdom.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p05] By the launch of the StrongARM J233 variant of the Risc PC in 1997, over 600,000 systems had been shipped running RISC OS, including Archimedes, A-series and Risc PC systems.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p05] The Archimedes was distributed to varying degrees outside the UK.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p05] Enquiries about the Archimedes range were reportedly handled for the US and Canada via Olivetti Canada, with distribution and servicing in Canada being undertaken by Comspec in association with Olivetti Canada.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p05] In Italy, the Archimedes was promoted and distributed by G.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p05] Ricordi & C., previously appointed as Acorn's exclusive distributor in the country.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p05] Acorn's original claims for the Archimedes noted a performance of 4 million instructions per second (MIPS), these reportedly being equivalent to DEC VAX-11/750 instructions.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p05] With the VAX-11/750 rated at 0.62 VAX MIPS, Acorn's claimed 4 MIPS translates crudely to around 2.5 VAX MIPS.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p05] This level of performance made the Archimedes one of the most powerful home computers available during the late 1980s and early 1990s, with its CPU outperforming the Motorola 68000 found in both the cheaper Amiga 500 and Atari ST machines as well as the more expensive Macintosh and Amiga 2000.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p05] Although an 8 MHz 68000 has a performance rating of around 1.2 VAX MIPS, the 68000-based Amiga 1000 reportedly achieved around 0.54 VAX MIPS when benchmarked as a system.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p05] In comparison, systems based on the 8 MHz ARM2, such as the BBC A3000, benchmarked from 2.7 VAX MIPS up to 3.4 VAX MIPS, depending on the operating system version and display configuration.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p05] Performance improvements would be delivered over time for the Archimedes and its competitors.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p05] For example, the Compaq Deskpro 386/16 model was replaced in 1988 with a 386/20 model offering somewhat improved CPU performance (around 3.5 VAX MIPS) and in 1989 by a 386/33 model improving CPU performance still further (to around 6.6 VAX MIPS).
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p05] The Macintosh II series incrementally improved their performance from around 1.6 VAX MIPS in 1987 with the original 68020-based model, through to around 6.1 VAX MIPS in the 68030-based Macintosh IIfx in 1990.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p05] ARM3 upgrades were initially rather expensive but decreased significantly in price and were available for all ARM2 systems, even the relatively inexpensive A3000.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p05] Thus, Acorn's ARM3-based machines, generally priced for business or institutional users, remained broadly competitive.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p05] Acorn's low-end A3010, fitted with an ARM250 processor, was capable of delivering from 3.1 VAX MIPS up to 5.0 VAX MIPS, remaining competitive with upgraded Amiga models such as the Amiga 2500.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p05] With ARM Limited focusing on embedded applications, it was noted that "the large performance lead Arm2 and Arm3 once enjoyed" over contemporary Intel processors was over, at least for the time being.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p05] The introduction of the 68040, and particularly the introduction of the 80486 with its subsequent evolution, put ARM3-based Archimedes models at an increasing performance disadvantage.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p05] Successors to the Macintosh II in the form of the Quadra and Centris series improved performance two- to four-fold over earlier models.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p05] Against such performance ratings only Acorn's Risc PC 600 (18.4 VAX MIPS to 21.8 VAX MIPS) fitted with an ARM610 CPU could keep up.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p05] However, by the time of its introduction in 1994, two years after the reported incorporation of the ARM610 in the Apple Newton, such performance had already been surpassed by Pentium-based models such as the Compaq Deskpro 5/66M Model 510 delivering 40.3 VAX MIPS.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p05] Already in 1988, a 20 MHz Compaq system with an 80386 CPU and 80387 co-processor would achieve around 1800 KWhetstones or around 20 times the performance of the ARM2 emulating floating-point instructions.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p05] Acorn's WE32206-based Floating Point Unit (FPU), available for the A400 series and R140, was expected to deliver ten-fold performance benefits, and was eventually claimed to offer eight-fold speed-ups.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p05] This left FPU-equipped systems delivering around half the performance of accelerated 386-based systems.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p05] For example, the MIPS R4400, available from 1992, achieved over 24 MFLOPS when benchmarked in systems.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p05] Continuing Acorn's involvement with the BBC and its computer literacy initiatives, two of the first Archimedes models bore the BBC branding, as did the later BBC A3000 model.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p05] Dissatisfaction with this arrangement was voiced by competitor Research Machines and an industry group led by a Microsoft representative, the British Micro Federation, who advocated the use of "business standard" operating systems such as MS-DOS.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p05] Responding to claims that the BBC branding was "unethical" and "damaging", a BBC Enterprises representative stated that the arrangement was "a continuing part of the original computer literacy project" and that bringing in "something totally new would be irresponsible".
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p05] The range won significant market share in the education markets of the UK, Ireland, Australia, and New Zealand.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p05] Over 15,000 schools registered to participate in the scheme and over 22 million vouchers were issued during the campaign period, placing the estimated value of the distributed products at over £4.5 million, although the actual value of distributed products was later reported as £3 million.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p05] Noting that the scheme was "not purely philanthropic", concern was expressed about the effect on the Acorn market and that schools were needing to "resort to charities and publicity stunts to get the basic tools to do the job".
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p05] In response to such criticism, independent software titles were dropped from the scheme in 1994, which ultimately distributed products to over 10,000 schools including 4,000 computers, with a total of 15,000 computers having been given away over the first three years of the scheme.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p05] With Tesco having expanded its presence in Scotland through acquisitions, the Tesco scheme was extended to Scotland for the first time in 1995.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p05] Alongside updates to the featured product selection, the possibility was introduced of saving unredeemed vouchers for redemption in the 1996 campaign.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p05] By the end of the 1996 campaign, £5.7 million worth of products had been distributed, with the scheme having distributed products worth a total of £25.9 million, including 26,000 Acorn computers in its first five years.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p05] By the mid to late 1990s, the UK educational market began to turn away from Acorn's products towards IBM PC compatibles, with Acorn and Apple establishing a joint venture, Xemplar, to market these companies' products in the education sector as part of a strategy to uphold their market share.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p05] Through Xemplar's involvement in the Computers for Schools scheme, Apple products were featured for the first time in the 1996 campaign.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p05] In 2000, Tesco changed its partner in the Computers for Schools scheme from Xemplar to RM plc.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p05] Acorn conducted other promotional initiatives towards the education sector.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p05] The Acorn Advantage programme, launched in September 1994, offered a loyalty scheme whereby points were accrued through purchases and redeemed for "curriculum resources" that included non-computing items such as musical and scientific instruments as well as computer hardware.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p05] Several commercial partners were involved in the scheme such as Fina, which awarded vouchers with petrol purchases that could be exchanged for points, and the Midland Bank which would donate points to schools joining its Midbank school-based banking system.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p05] An Acorn-branded Visa credit card would also generate Advantage points for nominated schools.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p05] The Archimedes was used by music composers and scorewriters to run the Sibelius scorewriting software.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p05] Between 1994 and 2004 the Archimedes and Risc PC models were used for teleprompters at television studios.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p05] The hardware was easy to adapt for TV broadcast use and cheaper than other hardware available at the time.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p05] Archimedes models saw use in other commercial broadcasting applications including scheduling and CD jukebox control for the Asda supermarket chain's in-store satellite broadcast radio channel.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p05] The performance and adaptability of the Archimedes range led these machines to be used in various entertainment venue applications and solutions.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p05] Laser Grafx's Prisma system employed Archimedes 440 and A5000 machines to control laser effects installations at music concerts and nightclubs.
[src:color-depth/acorn-archimedes-p05] A range of Archimedes and Risc PC models were used to control various aspects of the Quasar laser tag gaming experience, being introduced in an upgrade to the systems known as Chromaburst, itself subsequently being replaced by a more conservative solution using PC compatibles.
[src:color-depth/additive-color] Additive color models are applied in the design and testing of electronic displays that are used to render realistic images containing diverse sets of color using phosphors that emit light of a limited set of primary colors.
[src:color-depth/additive-color] Examination with a sufficiently powerful magnifying lens will reveal that each pixel in CRT, LCD, and most other types of color video displays is composed of red, green, and blue light-emitting phosphors which appear as a variety of single colors when viewed from a normal distance.
[src:color-depth/additive-color] Additive color, alone, does not predict the appearance of mixtures of printed color inks, dye layers in color photographs on film, or paint mixtures.
[src:color-depth/additive-color] Instead, subtractive color is used to model the appearance of pigments or dyes, such as those in paints and inks.
[src:color-depth/additive-color] The combination of two of the common three additive primary colors in equal proportions produces an additive secondary color—cyan, magenta or yellow.
[src:color-depth/additive-color] Additive color is also used to predict colors from overlapping projected colored lights often used in theatrical lighting for plays, concerts, circus shows, and night clubs.
[src:color-depth/additive-color] The full gamut of color available in any additive color system is defined by all the possible combinations of all the possible luminosities of each primary color in that system.
[src:color-depth/additive-color] In chromaticity space, a gamut is a plane convex polygon with corners at the primaries.
[src:color-depth/additive-color] Systems of additive color are motivated by the Young–Helmholtz theory of trichromatic color vision, which was articulated around 1850 by Hermann von Helmholtz, based on earlier work by Thomas Young.
[src:color-depth/additive-color] For his experimental work on the subject, James Clerk Maxwell is sometimes credited as being the father of additive color.
[src:color-depth/additive-color] He had the photographer Thomas Sutton photograph a tartan ribbon on black-and-white film three times, first with a red, then green, then blue color filter over the lens.
[src:color-depth/additive-color] The three black-and-white images were developed and then projected onto a screen with three different projectors, each equipped with the corresponding red, green, or blue color filter used to take its image.
[src:color-depth/additive-color] When brought into alignment, the three images (a black-and-red image, a black-and-green image and a black-and-blue image) formed a full-color image, thus demonstrating the principles of additive color.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Photoshop can edit and compose raster images in multiple layers and supports masks, alpha compositing and several color models.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Photoshop uses its own PSD and PSB file formats to support these features.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] In addition to raster graphics, Photoshop has limited abilities to edit or render text and vector graphics (especially through clipping path for the latter), as well as 3D graphics and video.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Its feature set can be expanded by plug-ins; programs developed and distributed independently of Photoshop that run inside it and offer new or enhanced features.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Photoshop's naming scheme was initially based on version numbers.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] However, in October 2002 (following the introduction of Creative Suite branding), each new version of Photoshop was designated with "**CS**" plus a number; e.g., the eighth major version of Photoshop was **Photoshop CS** and the ninth was **Photoshop CS2**.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Photoshop CS3 through CS6 were also distributed in two different editions: Standard and Extended.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] With the introduction of the Creative Cloud branding in June 2013 (and, in turn, the change of the "**CS**" suffix to "**CC**"), Photoshop's licensing scheme was changed to that of subscription model.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Historically, Photoshop was bundled with additional software such as Adobe ImageReady, Adobe Fireworks, Adobe Bridge, Adobe Device Central and Adobe Camera RAW.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Alongside Photoshop, Adobe also develops and publishes Photoshop Elements, Photoshop Lightroom, Photoshop Express, Photoshop Fix, Adobe Illustrator, and Photoshop Mix.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] As of November 2019, Adobe has also released a full version of Photoshop for the iPad, and while initially limited, Adobe plans to bring more features to Photoshop for iPad.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Collectively, they are branded as "The Adobe Photoshop Family".
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Photoshop was developed in 1987 by two brothers, Thomas and John Knoll, who sold the distribution license to Adobe Systems Incorporated in 1988.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Thomas Knoll, a Ph.D. student at the University of Michigan, began writing a program on his Macintosh Plus to display grayscale images on a monochrome display.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] This program (at that time called **Display**) caught the attention of his brother John, an Industrial Light & Magic employee, who recommended that Thomas turn it into a full-fledged image editing program.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Thomas took a six-month break from his studies in 1988 to collaborate with his brother on the program.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Thomas renamed the program ImagePro, but the name was already taken.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Later that year, Thomas renamed his program **Photoshop** and worked out a short-term deal with scanner manufacturer Barneyscan to distribute copies of the program with a slide scanner; a "total of about 200 copies of Photoshop were shipped" this way.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] During this time, John traveled to Silicon Valley and gave a demonstration of the program to engineers at Apple Computer and Russell Brown, art director at Adobe.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Both showings were successful, and Adobe decided to purchase the license to distribute in September 1988.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] While John worked on plug-ins in California, Thomas remained in Ann Arbor writing code.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] *Photoshop* 1.0 was released on February 19, 1990, for Macintosh exclusively.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] The Barneyscan version included advanced color editing features that were stripped from the first Adobe shipped version.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] The handling of color slowly improved with each release from Adobe and Photoshop quickly became the industry standard in digital color editing.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] When Photoshop 1.0 was released, digital retouching on dedicated high-end systems (such as the Scitex) cost around $300 an hour for basic photo retouching.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] The list price of Photoshop 1.0 for Macintosh in 1990 was $895.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Photoshop was initially only available on Macintosh.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] In 1993, Adobe chief architect Seetharaman Narayanan ported Photoshop to Microsoft Windows.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] The Windows port led to Photoshop reaching a wider mass market audience as Microsoft's global reach expanded within the next few years.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] On March 31, 1995, Adobe purchased the rights for Photoshop from Thomas and John Knoll for $34.5 million so Adobe would no longer need to pay a royalty for each copy sold.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Photoshop files have default file extension as .**PSD**, which stands for "**P**hoto**s**hop **D**ocument".
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] A PSD file stores an image with support for all features of Photoshop; these include layers with masks, transparency, text, alpha channels and spot colors, clipping paths, and duotone settings.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] This is in contrast to many other file formats (e.g., .JPG or .GIF) that restrict content to provide streamlined, predictable functionality.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] A PSD file has a maximum height and width of 30,000 pixels, and a size limit of two gigabytes.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] From the beginning, Photoshop could save files in other formats, including TIF, JPEG, and GIF.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] These files are smaller than PSD files because they lack the editable features of a PSD file.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] These formats are required to use the file in publications or on the web.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Adobe's discontinued program PageMaker required TIF format.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Photoshop can also create and use files with the extension .PSB, which stands for "Photoshop Big" (also known as "large document format").
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] A PSB file extends the PSD file format, increasing the maximum height and width to 300,000 pixels and the size limit to around 4 exabytes.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Because of Photoshop's popularity, PSD files are widely used and supported to some extent by most competing software, including GIMP, Affinity Photo, and Clip Studio Paint.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] The .PSD file format can be exported to and from Adobe's other apps, such as Adobe Illustrator, Adobe Premiere Pro, and After Effects.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Photoshop functionality can be extended by add-on programs called Photoshop plugins (or plug-ins).
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Adobe creates some, such as Adobe Camera Raw, but most are developed by third-parties.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Some are free and some are commercial software.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Most plugins work with only Photoshop or Photoshop-compatible hosts, but a few can also be run as standalone applications.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] There are various types of plugins, such as filter, export, import, selection, color correction, and automation.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] The most popular plugins are the filter plugins (also known as a 8bf plugins), available under the Filter menu in Photoshop.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Filter plugins can either modify the current image or create content.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Adobe Camera Raw (also known as ACR and Camera Raw) is a special plugin, supplied free by Adobe, used primarily to read and process raw image files so that the resulting images can be processed by Photoshop.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] It can also be used from within Adobe Bridge.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Photoshop's naming scheme was initially based on version numbers, from early pre-release builds and version 1.0 (February 1990) through version 7.0.1.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Adobe published seven major versions before the October 2003 introduction of version 8.0, which brought the *Creative Suite* branding.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Photoshop 1.0 was released in February 1990.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Photoshop 2.0 was released in June 1991.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] It added support for paths and the CMYK color model.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Photoshop 2.5, released in November 1992, was the first version available for Windows.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Photoshop 3.0 was released in September 1994 for Mac OS 7.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] The Windows version came out later in November.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Notably, this was the first version that brought *Layers*.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Photoshop 4.0 was released in November 1996.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Photoshop 6.0 was released in September 2000.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Photoshop 7.0 was released in March 2002.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] The first Photoshop CS was commercially released in October 2003 as the eighth major version of Photoshop.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Photoshop CS increased user control with a reworked file browser augmenting search versatility, sorting and sharing capabilities and the Histogram Palette which monitors changes in the image as they are made to the document.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Match Color was also introduced in CS, which reads color data to achieve a uniform expression throughout a series of pictures.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Photoshop CS2, released in May 2005, expanded on its predecessor with a new set of tools and features.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] It included an upgraded *spot healing brush*, which is mainly used for handling common photographic problems such as blemishes, red-eye, noise, blurring and lens distortion.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Adobe responded to feedback from the professional media industry by implementing non-destructive editing as well as the producing and modifying of 32-bit high dynamic range (HDR) images, which are optimal for 3D rendering and advanced compositing.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] FireWire previews could also be viewed on a monitor via a direct export feature.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Photoshop CS2 brought the *vanishing point* and *image warping* tools.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] *Vanishing point* tool makes tedious graphic and photo retouching endeavors much simpler by letting users clone, paint and transform image objects while maintaining visual perspective.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] *Image warping* tool makes it easy to digitally distort an image into a shape by choosing on-demand presets or by dragging control points.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] The file browser was upgraded to *Adobe Bridge*, which functioned as a hub for productivity, imagery and creativity, providing multi-view file browsing and smooth cross-product integration across Adobe Creative Suite 2 software.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Adobe Bridge also provided access to Adobe Stock Photos, a new stock photography service that offered users one-stop shopping across five elite stock image providers to deliver high-quality, royalty-free images for layout and design.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Photoshop CS2 brought a streamlined interface, making it easier to access features for specific instances.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] In CS2 users were also given the ability to create their own custom presets, which was meant to save time and increase productivity.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] CS3 and CS3 Extended were released in April 2007 to the United States and Canada.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] They were also made available through Adobe's online store and Adobe Authorized Resellers.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Both CS3 and CS3 Extended are offered as either a stand-alone application or feature of Adobe Creative Suite.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Both products are compatible with Intel-based Macs and PowerPCs, supporting Windows XP and Windows Vista.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] CS3 is the first release of Photoshop that will run natively on Macs with Intel processors: previous versions can only run through the translation layer Rosetta, and will not run at all on Macs running Mac OS X 10.7 or later.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] CS3 improves on features from previous versions of Photoshop and introduces new tools.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] One of the most significant is the streamlined interface which allows increased performance, speed, and efficiency.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] There is also improved support for Camera RAW files which allow users to process images with higher speed and conversion quality.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] CS3 supports over 150 RAW formats as well as JPEG, TIFF and PDF.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Enhancements were made to the Black and White Conversion, Brightness and Contrast Adjustment and Vanishing Point Module tools.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] The Black and White adjustment option improves control over manual grayscale conversions with a dialog box similar to that of Channel Mixer.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] There is more control over print options and better management with Adobe Bridge.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] The Clone Source palette is introduced, adding more options to the clone stamp tool.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Other features include the nondestructive Smart Filters, optimizing graphics for mobile devices, Fill Light and Dust Busting tools.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Compositing is assisted with Photoshop's new Quick Selection and Refine Edge tools and improved image stitching technology.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] CS3 Extended includes everything in CS3 and additional features.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] There are tools for 3D graphic file formats, video enhancement and animation, and comprehensive image measurement and analysis tools with DICOM file support.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] The 3D graphic formats allow 3D content to be incorporated into 2D compositions.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] As for video editing, CS3 supports layers and video formatting so users can edit video files per frame.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] CS4 and CS4 Extended were released on October 15, 2008.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Both CS4 and CS4 Extended are offered as either a stand-alone application or feature of Adobe Creative Suite.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Both products are compatible with Intel-based Mac OS X and PowerPCs, supporting Windows XP and Windows Vista.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] CS4 features smoother panning and zooming, allowing faster image editing at a high magnification.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] The interface is more simplified with its tab-based interface making it cleaner to work with.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Photoshop CS4 features a new 3D engine allowing the conversion of gradient maps to 3D objects, adding depth to layers and text, and getting print-quality output with the new ray-tracing rendering engine.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] It supports common 3D formats; the new Adjustment and Mask panels; content-aware scaling (seam carving); fluid canvas rotation and File display options.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] The content-aware scaling allows users to intelligently size and scale images, and the canvas rotation tool makes it easier to rotate and edit images from any angle.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Adobe released Photoshop CS4 Extended, which has the features of Adobe Photoshop CS4, plus capabilities for scientific imaging, 3D, motion graphics, accurate image analysis and high-end film and video users.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] The faster 3D engine allows users to paint directly on 3D models, wrap 2D images around 3D shapes and animate 3D objects.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] As the successor to Photoshop CS3, Photoshop CS4 is the first x64 edition of Photoshop on consumer computers for Windows.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] The color correction tool has also been improved significantly.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Photoshop CS5 was launched on April 12, 2010.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] In a video posted on its official Facebook page, the development team revealed the new technologies under development, including three-dimensional brushes and warping tools.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] In May 2011, Adobe Creative Suite 5.5 (CS5.5) was released, with new versions of some of the applications.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Its version of Photoshop, 12.1, is identical to the concurrently released update for Photoshop CS5, version 12.0.4, except for support for the new subscription pricing that was introduced with CS5.5.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] CS5 introduces new tools such as the Content-Aware Fill, Refine Edge, Mixer Brush, Bristle Tips and Puppet Warp.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] The community also had a hand in the additions made to CS5 as 30 new features and improvements were included by request.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] These include automatic image straightening, the Rule-of-Thirds cropping tool, color pickup, and saving a 16-bit image as a JPEG.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Another feature includes the Adobe Mini Bridge, which allows for efficient file browsing and management.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] CS5 Extended includes everything in CS5 plus features in 3D and video editing.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] A new materials library was added, providing more options such as Chrome, Glass, and Cork.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] The new Shadow Catcher tool can be used to further enhance 3D objects.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] For motion graphics, the tools can be applied to over more than one frame in a video sequence.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] CS5 and CS5 Extended were made available through Adobe's online store, Adobe Authorized Resellers and Adobe direct sales.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Both CS5 and CS5 Extended are offered as either a stand-alone application or a feature of Adobe Creative Suite 5.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Both products are compatible with Intel-based Mac OS X and Windows XP, Windows Vista, and Windows 7.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Photoshop CS6, released in May 2012, added new creative design tools and provided a redesigned interface with a focus on enhanced performance.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] New features have been added to the Content-Aware tool such as the Content-Aware Patch and Content-Aware Move.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Adobe Photoshop CS6 brought a suite of tools for video editing.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Color and exposure adjustments, as well as layers, are among a few things that are featured in this new editor.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Upon completion of editing, the user is presented with a handful of options of exporting into a few popular formats.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] CS6 brings the "straighten" tool to Photoshop, where a user simply draws a line anywhere on an image, and the canvas will reorient itself so that the line drawn becomes horizontal, and adjusts the media accordingly.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] This was created with the intention that users will draw a line parallel to a plane in the image, and reorient the image to that plane to more easily achieve certain perspectives.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] CS6 allows background saving, which means that while another document is compiling and archiving itself, it is possible to simultaneously edit an image.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] CS6 also features a customizable auto-save feature, preventing any work from being lost.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] With version 13.1.3, Adobe dropped support for Windows XP (including Windows XP Professional x64 Edition); thus, the last version that works on Windows XP is 13.0.1.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Adobe also announced that CS6 will be the last suite sold with perpetual licenses in favor of the new Creative Cloud subscriptions, though they will continue to provide OS compatibility support as well as bug fixes and security updates as necessary.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Starting January 9, 2017, CS6 is no longer available for purchase, making a Creative Cloud license the only purchase option going forward.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] No more updates will be available for all CS6 software either.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Photoshop CC (14.0) was launched on June 18, 2013.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] As the next major version after CS6, it is only available as part of a Creative Cloud subscription.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Major features in this version include new Smart Sharpen, Intelligent Upsampling, and Camera Shake Reduction for reducing blur caused by camera shake.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Editable Rounded Rectangles and an update to Adobe Camera Raw (8.0) were also included.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Since the initial launch, Adobe has released two additional feature-bearing updates.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] The first, version 14.1, was launched on September 9, 2013.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] The major features in this version were Adobe Generator, a Node.js-based platform for creating plug-ins for Photoshop.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Photoshop 14.1 shipped with two plug-ins, one to automatically generate image assets based on an extension in the layer name, and another to automatically generate assets for Adobe Edge Reflow.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Version 14.2 was released on January 15, 2014.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Major features include Perspective Warp, Linked Smart Objects, and 3D Printing support.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] CC 2014 features improvements to content-aware tools, two new blur tools (spin blur and path blur) and a new focus mask feature that enables the user to select parts of an image based on whether they are in focus or not.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Other minor improvements have been made, including speed increases for certain tasks.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Photoshop CC 2015 was released on June 15, 2015.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Adobe added various creative features including Adobe Stock, which is a library of custom stock images.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] It also includes and have the ability to have more than one layer style.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] For example, in the older versions of Photoshop, only one shadow could be used for a layer but in CC 2015, up to ten are available.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Other minor features like Export As, which is a form of the Save For Web in CC 2014 were also added.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] The updated UI as of November 30, 2015, delivers a cleaner and more consistent look throughout Photoshop, and the user can quickly perform common tasks using a new set of gestures on touch-enabled devices like Microsoft Surface Pro.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] CC 2015 also marks the 25th anniversary of Photoshop.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Photoshop CC 2017 was released on November 2, 2016.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] It introduced a new template selector when creating new documents, the ability to search for tools, panels and help articles for Photoshop, support for SVG OpenType fonts and other small improvements.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] In December 2016, a minor update was released to include support for the MacBook Pro Touch Bar.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Photoshop CC 2018 (version 19) was released on October 18, 2017.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] It featured an overhaul to the brush organization system, allowing for more properties (such as color and opacity) to be saved per-brush and for brushes to be categorized in folders and sub-folders.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] It also added brush stroke smoothing, and over 1000 brushes created by Kyle T.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Webster (following Adobe's acquisition of his website, KyleBrush.com).
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] A Curvature Pen tool, similar to the one in Illustrator, was added, allowing for faster creation of Bézier paths.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Photoshop CC 2019 was released on October 15, 2018.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Beginning with Photoshop CC 2019 (version 20.0), the 32-bit version of Windows is no longer supported.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] This version Introduced a new tool called Frame Tool to create placeholder frames for images.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] It also added multiple undo mode, auto-commitment, and prevented accidental panel moves with lock work-space.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Live blend mode previews are added, allowing for faster scrolling over different blend mode options in the layers panel.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Photoshop 2020 was released on November 4, 2019.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Version 21 has many new and enhanced features like the new object selection tool for better automation of complex selections, new properties panel, enhanced transform warp, new keyboard shortcuts for paint & brush and background image removal option.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] It added several improvements to the new content-aware fill and to the new document tab.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Also added were animated GIF support, improved lens blur performance and one-click zoom to a layer's contents.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] It introduced new swatches, gradients, patterns, shapes and stylistic sets for OpenType fonts.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] With this version users now can easily convert smart objects to layers and also can adjust 32-bit layers for brightness/contrast and curves.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Presets are now more intuitive to use and easier to organize.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] With the February 2020 update (version 21.1) Photoshop now can iteratively fill multiple areas of an image without having to leave content-aware fill workspace.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] This version improved GPU based lens blur quality and provided performance improvements, such as accelerating workflows with smoother panning, zooming and navigation of documents.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Version 21 was the first version where the iPad version was released.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] With Photoshop on the iPad, combined with the new Cloud PSD file format, a user can save cloud documents and work across Windows, Mac and iPad.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Photoshop on the iPad does not have all the features of the desktop Photoshop.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Adobe promises to update Photoshop on the iPad at "a much more aggressive pace than it has with its current Creative Cloud apps for the desktop".
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Adobe has provided a timeline for enhancing Photoshop on the iPad to have more of the features of desktop Photoshop.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Version 21.2 of the desktop version was released in June 2020.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] It introduced faster portrait selection, Adobe Camera Raw improvements, auto-activated Adobe Fonts, rotatable patterns, and improved Match Font.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Version 22.0.0 was released in October 2020.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Version 22.0.1 was released in November 2020.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Version 22.1.0 was released in December 2020.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Version 22.1.1 was released in January 2021.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Version 22.2 was released in February 2021.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Version 22.3 was released in March 2021.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] This is the first macOS release to run natively on Apple silicon.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Version 22.3.1 was released in April 2021.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Version 22.4.1 was released in May 2021.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Version 22.4.2 was released in June 2021.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Version 22.4.3 was released in July 2021.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Version 22.5 was released in August 2021.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Version 22.5.1 was released in September 2021.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Final version to include (as Legacy Swatches) a large set of Pantone color books, including Pastels & Neons, and Premium Metallics.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Version 23.0 was released in October 2021.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] First version to include (as Legacy Swatches) a reduced set of Pantone color books - only CMYK, Metallics and Solid colors.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Content Credentials (Beta) was introduced.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] When enabled, the editing information is captured in a tamper-evident form and resides with the file through successive copy generations.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] It aligns with the C2PA standard on digital provenance across the internet.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Version 23.0.1 was released in November 2021.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Version 23.0.2 was released in November 2021.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Version 23.1 was released in December 2021.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Version 23.1.1 was released in January 2022.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Version 23.2 was released in February 2022.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Version 23.3 was released in April 2022.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Version 23.5 was released in August 2022.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Final version with built-in support for basic Pantone colors - CMYK, Metallics and Solid (as Legacy Swatches).
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Future versions require a separate subscription to access Pantone colors.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Version 24.0 was released in October 2022.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] First version without built-in support for Pantone colors.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] All Pantone colors have been removed as of August 16, 2022.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Separate paid subscription now required to access Pantone Connect extension and download color "fandecks".
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Version 24.1 was released in December 2022.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Version 24.7 was released on July 27, 2023.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Version 25.0 was released in September 2023.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] This version added Generative Fill and Generative Expand for commercial use.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] This was the last version where the CPU requirements on the Intel platform were limited to only SSE 4.2 instructions, which meant the x86-64-v2 microarchitecture (Intel Nehalem and newer, AMD Bulldozer and newer).
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Version 26 was released in October 2024.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] The CPU requirements on the Intel platform have been increased to support AVX2 instructions, which means the x86-64-v3 microarchitecture (Intel Haswell and newer, AMD Excavator and newer).
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] The Adobe Photoshop family is a group of applications and services made by Adobe for the use of professional image editing.
[src:color-depth/adobe-photoshop] Several features of the Adobe Photoshop family are pixel manipulating, image organizing, photo retouching, and more.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] AMD's main products include microprocessors, embedded processors, and graphics processors for servers, workstations, PCs, and embedded system applications, as well as chipsets for motherboards.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] The company has also expanded into new markets, such as data centers, gaming, and high-performance computing.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] AMD's processors are used in a wide range of computing devices, including PCs, servers, laptops, and gaming consoles.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] Initially manufacturing its own processors, the company outsourced its manufacturing after GlobalFoundries was spun off in 2009.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] Through its Xilinx acquisition in 2022, AMD offers field-programmable gate array (FPGA) products.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] AMD was founded in 1969 by Jerry Sanders and a group of his fellow Fairchild Semiconductor colleagues.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] The company's early products were primarily memory chips and other computer components.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] In 1975, AMD entered the microprocessor market, competing with Intel, its main rival in the industry.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] In the early 2000s, it experienced significant growth and success, partly due to its strong position in the PC market and its Athlon and Opteron processors.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] The company faced challenges in the late 2000s and early 2010s, as it struggled to compete with Intel.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] In the late 2010s, AMD regained market share by pursuing a penetration pricing strategy for its Ryzen processors, offering a competitive performance and lower costs than Intel microprocessors.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] In 2022, AMD surpassed Intel by market capitalization for the first time.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] Advanced Micro Devices was formally incorporated by Jerry Sanders, along with seven of his colleagues from Fairchild Semiconductor—Ed Turney; John Carey; Sven Simonsen; Jack Gifford, and three members of his team: Frank Botte, Jim Giles, and Larry Stenger, on May 1, 1969.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] Sanders, an electrical engineer who was the director of marketing at Fairchild, had, like many of its executives, grown frustrated with the increasing lack of support, opportunity, and flexibility within the company.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] He later decided to leave to start his own semiconductor company, following the footsteps of Robert Noyce (developer of the first silicon integrated circuit at Fairchild in 1959) and Gordon Moore, who together founded the semiconductor company Intel in July 1968.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] In September 1969, AMD moved from its temporary location in Santa Clara to its new $500,000 15,000sqft headquarters at 901 Thompson Place, Sunnyvale, which housed the entire company, including the 8-mask, 7 μm feature size, 2-inch diameter wafer production.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] To immediately secure a customer base, AMD initially became a second source supplier of microchips designed by Fairchild (the 5 V TTL "9300" logic series) and National Semiconductor.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] AMD first focused on producing logic chips.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] In November 1969, the company manufactured its first product: the Am9300, a 4-bit MSI shift register, which began selling in 1970.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] Also in 1970, AMD produced its first proprietary product, the Am2501 logic counter, which was highly successful.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] Its bestselling product in 1971 was the Am2505, the fastest multiplier available.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] In 1971, AMD entered the RAM chip market, beginning with the Am3101, a 64-bit bipolar RAM.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] That year AMD also greatly increased the sales volume of its linear integrated circuits, and by year-end the company's total annual sales reached US$4.6 million.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] The company was a second source for Intel MOS/LSI circuits by 1973, with products such as Am14/1506 and Am14/1507, dual 100-bit dynamic shift registers.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] By 1975, AMD was producing 212 products – of which 49 were proprietary, including the Am9102 (a static N-channel 1024-bit RAM) and three low-power Schottky MSI circuits: Am25LS07, Am25LS08, and Am25LS09.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] Intel had created the first microprocessor, its 4-bit 4004, in 1971.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] By 1975, AMD entered the microprocessor market with the Am9080, a reverse-engineered clone of the Intel 8080, and the Am2900 bit-slice microprocessor family.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] When Intel began installing microcode in its microprocessors in 1976, it entered into a cross-licensing agreement with AMD, which was granted a copyright license to the microcode in its microprocessors and peripherals, effective October 1976.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] In 1977, AMD entered into a joint venture with Siemens, a German engineering conglomerate wishing to enhance its technology expertise and enter the American market.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] Siemens purchased 20% of AMD's stock, giving the company an infusion of cash to increase its product lines.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] The two companies also jointly established Advanced Micro Computers (AMC), located in Silicon Valley and in Germany, allowing AMD to enter the microcomputer development and manufacturing field, in particular based on AMD's second-source Zilog Z8000 microprocessors.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] When the two companies' vision for Advanced Micro Computers diverged, AMD bought out Siemens' stake in the American division in 1979.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] AMD closed Advanced Micro Computers in late 1981 after switching focus to manufacturing second-source Intel x86 microprocessors.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] Total sales in fiscal year 1978 topped $100 million, and in 1979, AMD debuted on the New York Stock Exchange.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] In 1979, production also began on AMD's new semiconductor fabrication plant in Austin, Texas; the company already had overseas assembly facilities in Penang and Manila, and began construction on a fabrication plant in San Antonio in 1981.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] In 1980, AMD began supplying semiconductor products for telecommunications, an industry undergoing rapid expansion and innovation.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] Intel had introduced the first x86 microprocessors in 1978.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] In 1981, IBM created its personal computer, and wanted Intel's x86 processors, but only under the condition that Intel would also provide a second-source manufacturer for its patented x86 microprocessors.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] Intel and AMD entered into a 10-year technology exchange agreement, first signed in October 1981 and formally executed in February 1982.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] The technical information and licenses needed to make and sell a part would be exchanged for a royalty to the developing company.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] The 1982 agreement also extended the 1976 AMD–Intel cross-licensing agreement through 1995.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] The agreement included the right to invoke arbitration of disagreements, and after five years the right of either party to end the agreement with one year's notice.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] The main result of the 1982 agreement was that AMD became a second-source manufacturer of Intel's x86 microprocessors and related chips, and Intel provided AMD with database tapes for its 8086, 80186, and 80286 chips.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] However, in the event of a bankruptcy or takeover of AMD, the cross-licensing agreement would be effectively canceled.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] Beginning in 1982, AMD began volume-producing second-source Intel-licensed 8086, 8088, 80186, and 80188 processors, and by 1984, its own Am286 clone of Intel's 80286 processor, for the rapidly growing market of IBM PCs and IBM clones.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] It also continued its successful concentration on proprietary bipolar chips.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] The company continued to spend greatly on research and development, and created the world's first 512K EPROM in 1984.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] That year, AMD was listed in the book *The 100 Best Companies to Work for in America*, and later made the *Fortune* 500 list for the first time in 1985.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] By mid-1985, the microchip market experienced a severe downturn, mainly due to long-term aggressive trade practices (dumping) from Japan, but also due to a crowded and non-innovative chip market in the United States.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] During this time, AMD withdrew from the DRAM market, and made some headway into the CMOS market, which it had lagged in entering, having focused instead on bipolar chips.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] AMD had some success in the mid-1980s with the AMD7910 and AMD7911 "World Chip" FSK modem, one of the first multi-standard devices that covered both Bell and CCITT tones at up to 1200 baud half duplex or 300/300 full duplex.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] Beginning in 1986, AMD embraced the perceived shift toward RISC with its own AMD Am29000 (29k) processor; the 29k survived as an embedded processor.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] The company also increased its EPROM memory market share in the late 1980s.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] Throughout the 1980s, AMD was a second-source supplier of Intel x86 processors.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] In 1991, it introduced its 386-compatible Am386, an AMD-designed chip.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] Creating its own chips, AMD began to compete directly with Intel.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] In January 1996, AMD acquired NexGen for $857 million to develop what eventually became AMD K6.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] At the time, NexGen was working on its Nx686 microprocessor.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] AMD had a large, successful flash memory business, even during the dotcom bust.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] In December 2005, AMD divested itself of Spansion to focus on the microprocessor market, and Spansion went public in an IPO.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] On July 24, 2006, AMD announced its acquisition of the Canadian 3D graphics card company ATI Technologies.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] AMD paid $4.3 billion and 58 million shares of its capital stock, for approximately $5.4 billion.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] The transaction was completed on October 25, 2006.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] On August 30, 2010, AMD announced that it would retire the ATI brand name for its graphics chipsets in favor of the AMD brand name.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] In October 2008, AMD announced plans to spin off manufacturing operations in the form of GlobalFoundries Inc., a multibillion-dollar joint venture with Advanced Technology Investment Co., an investment company formed by the government of Abu Dhabi.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] The partnership and spin-off gave AMD an infusion of cash and allowed it to focus solely on chip design.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] To assure the Abu Dhabi investors of the new venture's success, AMD's CEO Hector Ruiz stepped down in July 2008, while remaining executive chairman, in preparation for becoming chairman of GlobalFoundries in March 2009.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] President and COO Dirk Meyer became AMD's CEO.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] Recessionary losses necessitated AMD cutting 1,100 jobs in 2009.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] In August 2011, AMD announced that former Lenovo executive Rory Read would be joining the company as CEO, replacing Meyer.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] In November 2011, AMD announced plans to lay off more than 10% (1,400) of its employees from across all divisions worldwide.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] In October 2012, it announced plans to lay off an additional 15% of its workforce to reduce costs in the face of declining sales revenue.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] The inclusion of AMD chips into the PlayStation 4 and Xbox One were later seen as saving AMD from bankruptcy.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] AMD acquired the low-power server manufacturer SeaMicro in early 2012, with an eye to bringing out an Arm64 server chip.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] On October 8, 2014, AMD announced that Rory Read had stepped down after three years as president and chief executive officer.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] He was succeeded by Lisa Su, a key lieutenant who had been chief operating officer since June.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] On October 16, 2014, AMD announced a new restructuring plan along with its Q3 results.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] As part of this restructuring, AMD announced that 7% of its global workforce would be laid off by the end of 2014.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] After the GlobalFoundries spin-off and subsequent layoffs, AMD was left with significant vacant space at 1 AMD Place, its aging Sunnyvale headquarters office complex.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] In August 2016, AMD's 47 years in Sunnyvale came to a close when it signed a lease with the Irvine Company for a new 220,000 sq. ft. headquarters building in Santa Clara.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] AMD's new location at Santa Clara Square faces the headquarters of arch-rival Intel across the Bayshore Freeway and San Tomas Aquino Creek.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] Around the same time, AMD also agreed to sell 1 AMD Place to the Irvine Company.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] In April 2019, the Irvine Company secured approval from the Sunnyvale City Council of its plans to demolish 1 AMD Place and redevelop the entire 32-acre site into townhomes and apartments.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] In October 2020, AMD announced that it was acquiring Xilinx, the market leader in field programmable gate arrays and complex programmable logic devices (FPGAs and CPLDs) in an all-stock transaction.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] The acquisition was completed in February 2022, with an estimated acquisition price of $50 billion.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] In January 2024, AMD announced it was discontinuing the production of all complex programmable logic devices (CPLDs) acquired through Xilinx.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] In March 2024, a rally in semiconductor stocks pushed AMD's valuation above $300B for the first time.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] In July 2024, AMD announced that it would acquire the Finnish-based artificial intelligence start-up company Silo AI in a $665 million all-cash deal in an attempt to better compete with AI chip market leader Nvidia.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] In August 2024, AMD signed a deal to acquire ZT Systems for $4.9 billion.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] The company creates custom computing infrastructure that is used for AI tasks.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] Since early 2024, AMD has made significant gains in the server CPU market, reducing the gap with Intel.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] Initial reports of a 50:50 market split drew on incorrect data and were later revised.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] As of July 2025, Intel holds 63.3% of the server CPU market, while AMD has reached 36.5%, showing a strong upward trend for AMD despite Intel's continuing lead.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] In June 2025, AMD unveiled the AI server for 2026, the MI400 series of chips, which will be the basis of a new server called "Helios".
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] In October 2025, the company announced it had agreed a deal with OpenAI to sell six gigawatts of its AI processors over the next five years.
[src:color-depth/amd-p01] As part of the deal, OpenAI has the option to acquire a 10 per cent stake in AMD: 160 million shares at a token price of $0.01 per share contingent on meeting undisclosed performance targets, the final tranche of options requiring AMD common stock to reach $600 per share.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] In February 1982, AMD signed a contract with Intel, becoming a licensed second-source manufacturer of 8086 and 8088 processors.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] IBM wanted to use the Intel 8088 in its IBM PC, but its policy at the time was to require at least two sources for its chips.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] AMD later produced the Am286 under the same arrangement.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] In 1984, Intel internally decided to no longer cooperate with AMD in supplying product information to shore up its advantage in the marketplace, and delayed and eventually refused to convey the technical details of the Intel 80386.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] In 1987, AMD invoked arbitration over the issue, and Intel reacted by canceling the 1982 technological-exchange agreement altogether.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] After three years of testimony, AMD eventually won in arbitration in 1992, but Intel disputed this decision.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] Another long legal dispute followed, ending in 1994 when the Supreme Court of California sided with the arbitrator and AMD.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] In 1990, Intel countersued AMD, renegotiating AMD's right to use derivatives of Intel's microcode for its cloned processors.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] In the face of uncertainty during the legal dispute, AMD was forced to develop clean room designed versions of Intel code for its x386 and x486 processors, the former long after Intel had released its own x386 in 1985.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] In March 1991, AMD released the Am386, its clone of the Intel 386 processor.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] By October of the same year it had sold one million units.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] In 1993, AMD introduced the first of the Am486 family of processors, which proved popular with a large number of original equipment manufacturers, including Compaq, which signed an exclusive agreement using the Am486.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] The Am5x86, another Am486-based processor, was released in November 1995, and continued AMD's success as a fast, cost-effective processor.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] Finally, in an agreement effective 1996, AMD received the rights to the microcode in Intel's x386 and x486 processor families, but not the rights to the microcode in the following generations of processors.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] AMD's first in-house x86 processor was the K5, launched in 1996.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] The "K" in its name was a reference to Kryptonite, the only substance known to harm comic book character Superman.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] This itself was a reference to Intel's hegemony over the market, i.e., an anthropomorphization of them as Superman.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] The number "5" was a reference to the fifth generation of x86 processors; rival Intel had previously introduced its line of fifth-generation x86 processors as Pentium because the U.S.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] Trademark and Patent Office had ruled that mere numbers could not be trademarked.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] In 1996, AMD purchased NexGen, specifically for the rights to its Nx series of x86-compatible processors.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] AMD gave the NexGen design team their own building, left them alone, and gave them time and money to rework the Nx686.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] The result was the K6 processor, introduced in 1997.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] Although it was based on Socket 7, variants such as K6-III/450 were faster than Intel's Pentium II (sixth-generation processor).
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] The K7 was AMD's seventh-generation x86 processor, making its debut under the brand name Athlon on June 23, 1999.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] Unlike previous AMD processors, it could not be used on the same motherboards as Intel's, due to licensing issues surrounding Intel's Slot 1 connector, and instead used a Slot A connector, referenced to the Alpha processor bus.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] The Duron was a lower-cost and limited version of the Athlon (64 KB instead of 256 KB L2 cache) in a 462-pin socketed PGA (socket A) or soldered directly onto the motherboard.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] Sempron was released as a lower-cost Athlon XP, replacing Duron in the socket A PGA era.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] It has since been migrated upward to all new sockets, up to AM3.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] On October 9, 2001, the Athlon XP was released.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] On February 10, 2003, the Athlon XP with 512 KB L2 Cache was released.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] The technology was initially launched as the Opteron server-oriented processor on April 22, 2003.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] Shortly thereafter, it was incorporated into a product for desktop PCs, branded Athlon 64.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] On April 21, 2005, AMD released the first dual-core Opteron, an x86-based server CPU.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] A month later, it released the Athlon 64 X2, the first desktop-based dual-core processor family.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] In May 2007, AMD abandoned the string "64" in its dual-core desktop product branding, becoming Athlon X2, downplaying the significance of 64-bit computing in its processors.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] Further updates involved improvements to the microarchitecture, and a shift of the target market from mainstream desktop systems to value dual-core desktop systems.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] In 2008, AMD started to release dual-core Sempron processors exclusively in China, branded as the Sempron 2000 series, with lower HyperTransport speed and smaller L2 cache.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] AMD completed its dual-core product portfolio for each market segment.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] In September 2007, AMD released the first server Opteron K10 processors, followed in November by the Phenom processor for desktop.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] K10 processors came in dual-core, triple-core, and quad-core versions, with all cores on a single die.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] AMD released a new platform codenamed "Spider", which used the new Phenom processor, and an R770 GPU and a 790 GX/FX chipset from the AMD 700 chipset series.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] However, AMD built the Spider at 65nm, which was uncompetitive with Intel's smaller and more power-efficient 45nm.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] In January 2009, AMD released a new processor line dubbed Phenom II, a refresh of the original Phenom built using the 45 nm process.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] AMD's new platform, codenamed "Dragon", used the new Phenom II processor, and an ATI R770 GPU from the R700 GPU family, and a 790 GX/FX chipset from the AMD 700 chipset series.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] The Phenom II came in dual-core, triple-core and quad-core variants, all using the same die, with cores disabled for the triple-core and dual-core versions.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] The Phenom II resolved issues that the original Phenom had, including a low clock speed, a small L3 cache, and a Cool'n'Quiet bug that decreased performance.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] The Phenom II cost less but was not performance-competitive with Intel's mid-to-high-range Core 2 Quads.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] The Phenom II also enhanced its predecessor's memory controller, allowing it to use DDR3 in a new native socket AM3, while maintaining backward compatibility with AM2+, the socket used for the Phenom, and allowing the use of the DDR2 memory that was used with the platform.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] In April 2010, AMD released a new Phenom II Hexa-core (6-core) processor codenamed "Thuban".
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] This was a totally new die based on the hexa-core "Istanbul" Opteron processor.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] It included AMD's "turbo core" technology, which allows the processor to automatically switch from 6 cores to 3 faster cores when more pure speed is needed.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] The Magny Cours and Lisbon server parts were released in 2010.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] The Magny Cours part came in 8 to 12 cores and the Lisbon part in 4 and 6 core parts.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] Magny Cours is focused on performance while the Lisbon part is focused on high performance per watt.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] Magny Cours is an MCM (multi-chip module) with two hexa-core "Istanbul" Opteron parts.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] This will use a new socket G34 for dual and quad-socket processors and thus will be marketed as Opteron 61xx series processors.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] Lisbon uses socket C32 certified for dual-socket use or single socket use only and thus will be marketed as Opteron 41xx processors.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] Both will be built on a 45 nm SOI process.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] The initiative intended to move some of the processing originally done on the CPU (e.g. floating-point unit operations) to the GPU, which is better optimized for some calculations.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] The Fusion was later renamed the AMD APU (Accelerated Processing Unit).
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] Llano was AMD's first APU built for laptops.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] Llano was the second APU released, targeted at the mainstream market.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] It incorporated a CPU and GPU on the same die, and northbridge functions, and used "Socket FM1" with DDR3 memory.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] The CPU part of the processor was based on the Phenom II "Deneb" processor.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] AMD suffered an unexpected decrease in revenue based on production problems for the Llano.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] More AMD APUs for laptops running Windows 7 and Windows 8 OS are being used commonly.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] These include AMD's price-point APUs, the E1 and E2, and their mainstream competitors with Intel's Core i-series: The Vision A- series, the A standing for accelerated.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] These range from the lower-performance A4 chipset to the A6, A8, and A10.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] These all incorporate next-generation Radeon graphics cards, with the A4 utilizing the base Radeon HD chip and the rest using a Radeon R4 graphics card, with the exception of the highest-model A10 (A10-7300) which uses an R6 graphics card.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] Bulldozer was AMD's microarchitecture codename for server and desktop AMD FX processors, first released on October 12, 2011.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] This family 15h microarchitecture is the successor to the family 10h (K10) microarchitecture design.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] Bulldozer was a clean-sheet design, not a development of earlier processors.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] The core was specifically aimed at 10–125 W TDP computing products.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] AMD claimed dramatic performance-per-watt efficiency improvements in high-performance computing (HPC) applications with Bulldozer cores.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] While hopes were high that Bulldozer would bring AMD to be performance-competitive with Intel once more, most benchmarks were disappointing.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] In some cases the new Bulldozer products were slower than the K10 models they were built to replace.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] The Piledriver microarchitecture was the 2012 successor to Bulldozer, increasing clock speeds and performance relative to its predecessor.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] Piledriver would be released in AMD FX, APU, and Opteron product lines.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] Piledriver was subsequently followed by the Steamroller microarchitecture in 2013.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] Used exclusively in AMD's APUs, Steamroller focused on greater parallelism.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] In 2015, the Excavator microarchitecture replaced Piledriver.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] Expected to be the last microarchitecture of the Bulldozer series, Excavator focused on improved power efficiency.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] The Bobcat microarchitecture was revealed during a speech from Henri Richard, AMD executive vice-president, in Computex 2007, and was put into production during the first quarter of 2011.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] Based on the difficulty competing in the x86 market with a single core optimized for the 10–100 W range, AMD had developed a simpler core with a target range of 1–10 watts.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] In addition, it was believed that the core could migrate into the hand-held space if the power consumption can be reduced to less than 1 W.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] Jaguar is a microarchitecture codename for Bobcat's successor, released in 2013, that is used in various APUs from AMD aimed at the low-power/low-cost market.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] Jaguar and its derivates would go on to be used in the custom APUs of the PlayStation 4, Xbox One, PlayStation 4 Pro, Xbox One S, and Xbox One X.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] Jaguar would be later followed by the Puma microarchitecture in 2014.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] In 2012, AMD announced it was working on ARM products, both as a semi-custom product and server product.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] The initial server product was announced as the Opteron A1100 in 2014, an 8-core Cortex-A57-based ARMv8-A SoC, and was expected to be followed by an APU incorporating a Graphics Core Next GPU.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] However, the Opteron A1100 was not released until 2016, with the delay attributed to adding software support.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] The A1100 was also criticized for not having support from major vendors upon its release.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] In 2014, AMD also announced the K12 custom core for release in 2016.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] While being ARMv8-A instruction set architecture compliant, the K12 was expected to be entirely custom-designed, targeting the server, embedded, and semi-custom markets.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] While ARM architecture development continued, products based on K12 were subsequently delayed with no release planned.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] Development of AMD's x86-based Zen microarchitecture was preferred.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] Zen is an architecture for x86-64 based Ryzen series of CPUs and APUs, introduced in 2017 by AMD and built from the ground up by a team led by Jim Keller, beginning with his arrival in 2012, and taping out before his departure in September 2015.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] One of AMD's primary goals with Zen was an IPC increase of at least 40%, however in February 2017 AMD announced that it had actually achieved a 52% increase.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] Processors made on the Zen architecture are built on the 14 nm FinFET node and have a renewed focus on single-core performance and HSA compatibility.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] Previous processors from AMD were either built in the 32 nm process ("Bulldozer" and "Piledriver" CPUs) or the 28 nm process ("Steamroller" and "Excavator" APUs).
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] Because of this, Zen is much more energy efficient.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] The Zen architecture is the first to encompass CPUs and APUs from AMD built for a single socket (Socket AM4).
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] Also new for this architecture is the implementation of simultaneous multithreading (SMT) technology, something Intel has had for years on some of its processors with its proprietary hyper-threading implementation of SMT.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] This is a departure from the "Clustered MultiThreading" design introduced with the Bulldozer architecture.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] AMD released the Zen-based high-end Ryzen 7 "Summit Ridge" series CPUs on March 2, 2017, mid-range Ryzen 5 series CPUs on April 11, 2017, and entry level Ryzen 3 series CPUs on July 27, 2017.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] AMD later released the Epyc line of Zen derived server processors for 1P and 2P systems.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] In October 2017, AMD released Zen-based APUs as Ryzen Mobile, incorporating Vega graphics cores.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] In January 2018, AMD announced its new lineup plans, with Ryzen 2.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] AMD launched CPUs with the 12nm Zen+ microarchitecture in April 2018, following up with the 7nm Zen 2 microarchitecture in June 2019, including an update to the Epyc line with new processors using the Zen 2 microarchitecture in August 2019, and Zen 3 slated for release in Q3 2020.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] As of 2019, AMD's Ryzen processors were reported to outsell Intel's consumer desktop processors.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] At CES 2020 AMD announced its Ryzen Mobile 4000, as the first 7 nm x86 mobile processor, the first 7 nm 8-core (also 16-thread) high-performance mobile processor, and the first 8-core (also 16-thread) processor for ultrathin laptops.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] This generation is still based on the Zen 2 architecture.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] In October 2020, AMD announced new processors based on the Zen 3 architecture.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] On PassMark's Single thread performance test the Ryzen 5 5600x bested all other CPUs besides the Ryzen 9 5950X.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] In April 2020, AMD launched three new SKUs which target commercial HPC workloads & hyperconverged infrastructure applications.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] The launch was based on Epyc's 7 nm second-generation Rome platform and supported by Dell EMC, Hewlett Packard Enterprise, Lenovo, Supermicro, and Nutanix.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] IBM Cloud was its first public cloud partner.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] In August 2022, AMD announced its initial lineup of CPUs based on the new Zen 4 architecture.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] The Steam Deck, PlayStation 5, Xbox Series X and Series S all use chips based on the Zen 2 microarchitecture, with proprietary tweaks and different configurations in each system's implementation than AMD sells in its own commercially available APUs.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] Lee Ka Lau, Francis Lau, Benny Lau, and Kwok Yuen Ho founded ATI in 1985 as Array Technology Incorporated, renamed later Array Technologies Incorporated and finally ATI Technologies.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] Working primarily in the OEM field, ATI produced integrated graphics cards for PC manufacturers such as IBM and Commodore.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] By 1987, ATI had grown into an independent graphics-card retailer, introducing EGA Wonder and VGA Wonder card product lines that year.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] In the early nineties, they released products able to process graphics without the CPU: in May 1991, the Mach8, in 1992 the Mach32, which offered improved memory bandwidth and GUI acceleration.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] ATI Technologies went public in 1993, with shares listed on NASDAQ and on the Toronto Stock Exchange.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] In 1994, the Mach64 accelerator debuted, powering the Graphics Xpression and Graphics Pro Turbo, offering hardware support for YUV-to-RGB colour space conversion in addition to hardware zoom; early techniques of hardware-based video acceleration.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] ATI introduced its first combination of 2D and 3D accelerator under the name 3D Rage.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] This chip was based on the Mach 64, but it featured elemental 3D acceleration.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] The ATI Rage line powered almost the entire range of ATI graphics products.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] In particular, the Rage Pro was one of the first viable 2D-plus-3D alternatives to 3dfx's 3D-only Voodoo chipset.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] 3D acceleration in the Rage line advanced from the basic functionality within the initial 3D Rage to a more advanced DirectX 6.0 accelerator in 1999 Rage 128.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] The All-in-Wonder product line, introduced in 1996, was the first combination of integrated graphics chip with TV tuner card and the first chip that enabled display of computer graphics on a TV set.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] The cards featured 3D acceleration powered by ATI's 3D Rage II, 64-bit 2D performance, TV-quality video acceleration, analogue video capture, TV tuner functionality, flicker-free TV-out and stereo TV audio reception.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] ATI entered the mobile computing sector by introducing 3D-graphics acceleration to laptops in 1996.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] The Mobility product line had to meet requirements different from those of desktop PCs, such as minimized power usage, reduced heat output, TMDS output capabilities for laptop screens, and maximized integration.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] In 1997, ATI acquired Tseng Labs's graphics assets, which included 40 engineers.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] The Radeon line of graphics products was unveiled in 2000.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] The initial Radeon GPU offered an all-new design with DirectX 7.0 3D acceleration, video acceleration, and 2D acceleration.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] Technology developed for a specific Radeon generation could be built in varying levels of features and performance in order to provide products suited for the entire market range, from high-end to budget to mobile versions.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] In 2000, ATI acquired ArtX, which engineered the Flipper graphics chip used in the GameCube video game console.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] They also created a modified version of the chip (codenamed Hollywood) for the successor of the GameCube, the Wii.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] Microsoft contracted ATI to design the graphics core (codenamed Xenos) for the Xbox 360.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] Later in 2005, ATI acquired Terayon's cable modem silicon intellectual property, strengthening their lead in the consumer digital television market.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] Ho remained as chairman of the board until he retired in November 2005.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] Dave Orton replaced him as the president and CEO of the organization.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] On July 24, 2006, a joint announcement revealed that AMD would acquire ATI in a deal valued at $5.6 billion.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] The acquisition consideration closed on October 25, 2006, and included over $2 billion financed from a loan and 56 million shares of AMD stock.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] ATI's operations became part of the AMD Graphics Product Group (GPG), and ATI's CEO Dave Orton became the executive vice president of Visual and Media Businesses at AMD until his resignation in 2007.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] The top-level management was reorganized with the senior vice president and general manager, and the senior vice president and general manager of Consumer Electronics Group, both of whom would report to the CEO of AMD.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] On August 30, 2010, John Trikola announced that AMD would retire the ATI brand for its graphics chipsets in favour of the AMD name.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] In 2007, the ATI division of AMD released the TeraScale microarchitecture implementing a unified shader model.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] This design replaced the previous fixed-function hardware of previous graphics cards with multipurpose, programmable shaders.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] Initially released as part of the GPU for the Xbox 360, this technology would go on to be used in Radeon branded HD 2000 parts.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] Three generations of TeraScale would be designed and used in parts from 2007 to 2015.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] In a 2009 restructuring, AMD merged the CPU and GPU divisions to support the company's APUs, which fused both graphics and general purpose processing.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] In 2011, AMD released the successor to TeraScale, Graphics Core Next (GCN).
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] This new microarchitecture emphasized GPGPU compute capability in addition to graphics processing, with a particular aim of supporting heterogeneous computing on AMD's APUs.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] GCN's reduced instruction set ISA allowed for significantly increased compute capability over TeraScale's very long instruction word ISA.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] Since GCN's introduction with the HD 7970, five generations of the GCN architecture have been produced from 2011 through at least 2018.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] In September 2015, AMD separated the graphics technology division of the company into an independent internal unit called the Radeon Technologies Group (RTG), headed by Raja Koduri.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] This gave the graphics division of AMD autonomy in product design and marketing.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] The RTG then went on to create and release the Polaris and Vega microarchitectures released in 2016 and 2017, respectively.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] In particular the Vega, or fifth-generation GCN, microarchitecture includes a number of major revisions to improve performance and compute capabilities.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] In November 2017, Raja Koduri left RTG and CEO and President Lisa Su took his position.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] In January 2018, it was reported that two industry veterans joined RTG, namely Mike Rayfield as senior vice president and general manager of RTG, and David Wang as senior vice president of engineering for RTG.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] In January 2020, AMD announced that its second-generation RDNA graphics architecture was in development, with the aim of competing with the Nvidia RTX graphics products for performance leadership.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] In October 2020, AMD announced its new RX 6000 series series GPUs, their first high-end product based on RDNA2 and capable of handling ray-tracing natively, aiming to challenge Nvidia's RTX 3000 GPUs.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] In 2012, AMD's then CEO Rory Read began a program to offer semi-custom designs.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] Rather than AMD simply designing and offering a single product, potential customers could work with AMD to design a custom chip based on AMD's intellectual property.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] Customers pay a non-recurring engineering fee for design and development, and a purchase price for the resulting semi-custom products.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] In particular, AMD noted its unique position of offering both x86 and graphics intellectual property.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] These semi-custom designs would have design wins as the APUs in the PlayStation 4 and Xbox One and the subsequent PlayStation 4 Pro, Xbox One S, Xbox One X, Xbox Series X/S, and PlayStation 5.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] Financially, these semi-custom products would represent a majority of the company's revenue in 2016.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] In November 2017, AMD and Intel announced that Intel would market a product combining in a single package an Intel Core CPU, a semi-custom AMD Radeon GPU, and HBM2 memory.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] Before the launch of Athlon 64 processors in 2003, AMD designed chipsets for its processors spanning the K6 and K7 processor generations.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] The chipsets include the AMD-640, AMD-751, and the AMD-761 chipsets.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] The situation changed in 2003 with the release of Athlon 64 processors, and AMD chose not to further design its own chipsets for its desktop processors while opening the desktop platform to allow other firms to design chipsets.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] This was the "Open Platform Management Architecture" with ATI, VIA and SiS developing its own chipset for Athlon 64 processors and later Athlon 64 X2 and Athlon 64 FX processors, including the Quad FX platform chipset from Nvidia.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] The initiative went further with the release of Opteron server processors as AMD stopped the design of server chipsets in 2004 after releasing the AMD-8111 chipset, and again opened the server platform for firms to develop chipsets for Opteron processors.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] As of today, Nvidia and Broadcom are the sole designing firms of server chipsets for Opteron processors.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] As the company completed the acquisition of ATI Technologies in 2006, the firm gained the ATI design team for chipsets which previously designed the Radeon Xpress 200 and the Radeon Xpress 3200 chipsets.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] AMD then renamed the chipsets for AMD processors under AMD branding (for instance, the CrossFire Xpress 3200 chipset was renamed as AMD 580X CrossFire chipset).
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] In February 2007, AMD announced the first AMD-branded chipset since 2004 with the release of the AMD 690G chipset (previously under the development codename *RS690*), targeted at mainstream IGP computing.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] It was the industry's first to implement a HDMI 1.2 port on motherboards, shipping for more than a million units.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] While ATI had aimed at releasing an Intel IGP chipset, the plan was scrapped and the inventories of Radeon Xpress 1250 (codenamed *RS600*, sold under ATI brand) was sold to two OEMs, Abit and ASRock.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] Although AMD stated the firm would still produce Intel chipsets, Intel had not granted the license of 1333 MHz FSB to ATI.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] On November 15, 2007, AMD announced a new chipset series portfolio, the AMD 7-Series chipsets, covering from the enthusiast multi-graphics segment to the value IGP segment, to replace the AMD 480/570/580 chipsets and AMD 690 series chipsets, marking AMD's first enthusiast multi-graphics chipset.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] Discrete graphics chipsets were launched on November 15, 2007, as part of the codenamed *Spider* desktop platform, and IGP chipsets were launched at a later time in spring 2008 as part of the codenamed *Cartwheel* platform.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] AMD returned to the server chipsets market with the AMD 800S series server chipsets.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] It includes support for up to six SATA 6.0 Gbit/s ports, the C6 power state, which is featured in Fusion processors and AHCI 1.2 with SATA FIS-based switching support.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] This is a chipset family supporting Phenom processors and Quad FX enthusiast platform (890FX), IGP (890GX).
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] With the advent of AMD's APUs in 2011, traditional northbridge features such as the connection to graphics and the PCI Express controller were incorporated into the APU die.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] Accordingly, APUs were connected to a single chip chipset, renamed the Fusion Controller Hub (FCH), which primarily provided southbridge functionality.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] AMD released new chipsets in 2017 to support the release of its new Ryzen products.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] As the Zen microarchitecture already includes much of the northbridge connectivity, the AM4-based chipsets primarily varied in the number of additional PCI Express lanes, USB connections, and SATA connections available.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] These AM4 chipsets were designed in conjunction with ASMedia.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] In the early 1990s, AMD began marketing a series of embedded system-on-a-chips (SoCs) called AMD Élan, starting with the SC300 and SC310.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] Both combines a 32-Bit, Am386SX, low-voltage 25 MHz or 33 MHz CPU with memory controller, PC/AT peripheral controllers, real-time clock, PLL clock generators and ISA bus interface.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] The SC300 integrates in addition two PC card slots and a CGA-compatible LCD controller.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] They were followed in 1996 by the SC4xx types, now supporting VESA Local Bus and using the Am486 with up to 100 MHz clock speed.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] An SC450 at 33 MHz, for example, was used in the Nokia 9110 Communicator.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] Using an Am586 with 100 MHz or 133 MHz and supporting SDRAM and PCI it was the latest member of the series.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] In February 2002, AMD acquired Alchemy Semiconductor for its Alchemy line of MIPS processors for the hand-held and portable media player markets.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] On June 13, 2006, AMD officially announced that the line was to be transferred to Raza Microelectronics, Inc., a designer of MIPS processors for embedded applications.
[src:color-depth/amd-p02] In August 2003, AMD also purchased the Geode business which was originally the Cyrix MediaGX from National Semiconductor to augment its existing line of embedded x86 processor products.
